column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 2:15 PM ON THURSDAY, 10/06/94 A DRIVER CALLED IN REPORTING THAT THERE WERE VAPORS AND A STRONG ODOR COMING FROM HIS TRAILER WHICH WAS PULLED UP TO A SAFE LOCATION.  HE THEN NOTICED A SMALL DRIP COMING FROM THE TRAILER.  THE PRODUCT DRIPPING WAS CAPTURED IN A SMALL RECOVERY UNIT.  THE ONLY SHIPMENT ON THE TRAILER ORIGANATED FRON VAN WATERS AND ROGERS WHO IDENTIFIED THE LEAKING PRODUCT AS HYDROCHLORIC ACID. VAN WATERS & ROGERS PROVIDED THE PERSONNEL TO LOCATED THE LEAKING CONTAINER, STOP THE LEAK, AND STABLILZE THE CONTAINER.  THEY THEN NEUTRALIZED THE SPILLED PRODUCT WITH SODE ASH.  THE LEAKING CONTAINER WAS IDENTIFIED AS A 15 GALLON POLYETHYLENE DRUM WHICH HAD BEEN PUNCTURED BY A NAIL PROTRUDING FROM THE PALLET THE PRODUCT HAD BEEN SHIPPED ON.  ONCE THE CONTAINER WAS STABLIZED AND THE SPILL NEUTRALIZED, THE TRAILER WAS MOVED TO VAN WATER & ROGERS WHERE THE PRODUCT WAS REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER AND THE TRAILER WAS CLEANED.  THE DAMAGED DRUM AND THE CLEANUP MATERIAL WAS RETAINED BY VAN WATERS & ROGERS FOR DISPOSAL.

AT APPROXIMATELY 8:40 A.M. ON FRIDAY, OCTOBER 7, 1994, AN N&M DRIVER CALLED THE SAFETY OFFICE TO REPORT THAT WHILE HIS TRAILER WAS PARKED ON AN INCLINE, HE NOTICED A SMALL DRIP OF LIQUID COMING FROM HIS TRAILER.  ONCE THE TRAILER WAS PULLED ON TO A LEVEL AREA, THE DRIPPING STOPPED.  THE DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO PULL HIS TRAILER INTO A DOCK (TNT- MCCOOK, IL) TO ENABLE AN INSPECTION OF THIS LOAD.  THE FREIGHT CONSISTED OF PAPER PRODUCTS ON PALLETS AND 66 DRUMS OF A FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  THE DRIVER HAD ORIGINALLY CONCLUDED FROM HIS INITIAL INSPECTION THAT ONE DRUM MUST HAVE BEEN PUNCTURED WHILE IT WAS TRANSFERED AT THE N&M TERMINAL.  HOWEVER, AFTER THE TRAILER ARRIVED BACK AT N&M, FURTHER INVESTIGATION BY THE N&M SAFETY MANAGER REVEALED THAT THE BOTTOM OF THIS DRUM WAS CORRODED, AND AS A RESULT, A CRACK DEVELOPED IN THE BOTTOM CENTER OF THE DRUM.  THE LEAKING PRODUCT WAS CONFINED TO A 5 FT AREA OF THE TRAILER FLOOR.  ONCCE THE PAPER PRODUCT WAS REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER, FLOOR DRY WAS USED TO ABSORB THE LIQUID.  THE FLOOR DRY WAS THEN PLACED IN A 55 GALLON DRUM FOR PROPER HAZARDOUS WASTE DISPOSAL.  THE TRAILER FLOOR WAS DECONTAMINATED AT THE N & M FACILITY.

TRAIN CREW MEMBER WAS MAKING A COUPLING, RUBBER DISC IN THE DOME OF TANK CAR GATX16571 WAS RUPTURED CAUSING SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION TO SPRAY OUT THE TOP OF THE RAIL CAR.  TRAIN CREW MEMBER WAS SPRAYED ON HIS BACK.  HE RECIEVED FIRST AID AT METHODIST NORTH HOSPITAL FOR SKIN IRRITATION.

LIQUID HYDROGEN CARGO TRAILER, SN613022, WAS OUTBOUND FROM THE PACE, FLORIDA, TERMINAL WHEN THE DRIVERS NOTICED A PRESSURE RISE DURING A SAFETY CHECK.  THE DRIVERS CALLED IN AND WERE INSTRUCTED TO RETURN TO THE TERMINAL (ABOUT 20 MILES FROM THE TERMINAL).  THE DRIVERS AGAIN STOPPED TO CHECK THE TRAILER PRESSURE AND REALIZED A RELEASE WAS EMMINENT.  THE TERMINAL WAS CALLED AND THE DRIVERS WERE INSTRUCTED TO SECURE THE TRAILER IN A REMOTE LOCATION AND CONTROL THE TRAILER PRESSURE UNTIL TERMINAL PERSONNEL COULD RESPOND.  AFTER THE ARRIVAL OF TERMIANL PERSONNEL, THE TRAILER WAS VENTED AND STABILIZED AT 5 POUNDS OF PRESSURE.  SUBSEQUENT INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE TRAILER HAD BEEN OVERLOADED BY THE PLANT OPERATOR RESULTING IN THE PRESSURE RISE.  TRAINING AND LOADING PROCEDURES HAVE BEEN REVIEWED AND PERSONNEL RETRAINED TO PREVENT ANY REOCCURANCE OF THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT.

GLASS BOTTLES IN PLASTICS BAG IN FIBREBOARD BOX-VERMICULITE WAS IN BOX. PACKAGING WAS EXCELLENT-IT APPEARS TOP MAY HAVE COME LOOSE.  LIQUID WAS ABSORBED BY THE BOX.  PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM & THE SHIPMENT MOVED ON THE CONSIGNEE.
PACKAGE WAS DROPPED APPROXIMATELY 3 FEET. GLASS BOTTLE BROKE.  THERE WAS NO ABSORBANT OR CUSHIONING MATERIAL IN THE PACKAGE.  BOX WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED.

AS THE BOX WAS UNLOADED IT WAS DROPPED.  UPON HITTING THE GROUND, THE INNER BOTTLE BROKE, SPILLING ITS CONTENTS.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP. THE BOX WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND IS AWAITING A DISPOSITION.

A STRONG ODOR WAS NOTICED DURING THE OFF LOAD PROCESS.  THE PACKAGINGS WERE CLOSLEY SCRUNTINIZED BUT NO LEAK WAS FOUND.  THE OTHER CONTENTS WERE ALSO CHECKED, BUT AGAIN NO LEAKS.  THE FREIGHT WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND SENTON TO THE ERECIPIENT.

THE DRUM WAS ALLEGEDLY DROPPED DURING THE SORT, UPON HITTING THE GROUND, THREE OF THE BOTTLES CRACKED AND DUMPED THEIR CONTENTS.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH BAKING SODA.  THE FIBER DRUM WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND HELD FOR A DISPOSITION.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: THE BOX WAS BROUGHT TO OUR DANGEROUS GOODS OFFICE BY AN OUTBOUND. DANGEROUS GOODS SPECIALIST.  THE PACKAGE WAS REMOVED FROM THE SORT DUE TO STRONG ODORS.  THE INNER DRUM WAS INSPECTED AND NO LEAKS WERE FOUND.  I SPOKE TO THE SHIPPER THIS MORNING AND ADIVSED THAT WE HAD THIS PROBLEM. THE BOX WAS PLACED IN A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM AND FORWARDED TO THE RECIPIENT.

THE BOX WAS STRUCK BY A DIVERTER ARM IN THE HUB SORT.  THE INNER BOTTLE WAS DAMAGED AND BEGAN TO LEAK.  ALL OF THE LEAKED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED TO THE BOX.  PACKING INSTRUCTION 611 LIMITS THE AMOUNT OF MATERIAL PER INNER PACKAGE TO 2.5L.  THE INNER PACKAGE IN THIS BOX WAS AL, FULLY 1.5 L MORE THAN WHAT IS ALLOWED.  THE SHIPPER HAS BEEN NOTIFIED AS HAS THE FAA IN NASHVILLE.  THE BOX WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND IS BEING HELD IN THE MEMPHIS HUB FOR INSPECTION BY THE FAA.

column17: HUNT J B SPECIAL COMMODITIES I
column168: DRIVER DISCOVERED FOUR DRUMS LEAKING FROM AROUND THE BUNG CLOSURES. DRIVER TIGHTENED THE CLOSURES ON THE DRUMS AND ABSORBED ALL SPILLED MATERIAL.  ALL SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED AND ALL RESIDUE FROM THE SPILL WAS ACCEPTED FOR DISPOSAL AT THE RECEIVER.

OPERATOR WAS ATTEMPTING TO LOAD TANK CAR FROM ABOVE GROUND TANK.  OPERATOR NOTICED THAT NO MATERIAL WAS BEING DRAWN FROM ABOVE GROUND TANK, SO HE REVERSED HIS PUMP, PUTTING PRESSURE ON TRANSFER HOSE.  THE TRANSFER HOSE FAILED & RESIDUE INSIDE HOSE WAS FORCED OUT.  ALL MATERIAL SPILLED ONTO SECONDARY CONTAINMENT.  TOTAL SPILL WAS RECOVERED WITH ABSORBENT SHEETS. NOTE SINCE NO LOAD WAS GENERATED THERE IS NO SHIPPING PAPER.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column17: HUNT J B SPECIAL COMMODITIES I
column168: DRIVER DISCOVERED FLUID IN THE TRAILER FLOOR WHEN HE CHECKED THE LOAD AFTER FUELING.  INSPECTION OF THE DRUMS REVEALED ONE DRUM AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER THAT HAD BEEN DAMAGED DURING LOADING.  THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO OVERPACK THE DRUM AND PUT ABSORBENT ON THE SPILLED MATERIAL.  ALL ABSORBENT USED TO CLEAN THE SPILL WAS ALSO PLACED IN AN OVERPACK FOR DISPOSAL AT THE RECEIVER.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: UPON UNLOADED TRAILER 48-391, THE DOCK WORKER DISCOVERED A 55-GALLON DRUM LEAKING.  SINCE IT WAS LOADED ON THE REAR OF THE TRAILER IT SMASHED INTO ANOTHER PALLET PUTTING A CREASE IN THE SIDE OF THE DRUM.  ONLY A SMALL AMOUNT APPEARED TO HAVE LEAKED OUT, THE DRUM, THE DRUM WAS TIPPED ONTO IT'S SIDE AND WAS REPORTED TO THE DOCK SUPERVISOR IMMEDIATLEY.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM AMOCO CORPORATION AMOCO OIL COMPANY LOCATED AT 5135 SIMPSON FERRY ROAD MECHANICSBURG, PA TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE, INC. LOCATED AT 1910 RUSSELL STREET IN BALTIMORE, MD.  DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBOR'S DEPTFORD SERVICE CENTER LOCATED AT 2301 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE IN DEPTFORD, NJ IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM A PINHOLE LEAK ON THE BOTTOM OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY ABOSRBED ALL FREE LIQUID WITH SPEEDI DRY AND OVERPACKED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM.  ALL CLEAN UP DEBRIS WAS PLACED IN THE SALVAGE DRUM AND WAS DISPOSED OF THROUGHT THE WASTE FACILITY INDICATED ON THE SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPERS LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AN NO EVIDENCE OF A LEAKING CONTAINER WAS OBSERVED.  ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

DRIVER UNLOADING AT CUSTOMER.  ACCORDING TO STICK READINGS THOUGHT LOAD WOULD FIT; APPROXIMATELY 40 TO 50 GALLONS SPILLED.  LOCAL CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR WAS CONTACTED TO HELP CLEAN-UP THE SPILL.  DID NOT ENTER SEWERS OR WATERWAYS.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: OUR DRIVER WAS MAKING A DELIVERY OF PREMIUM GASOLINE AT CLARK STATION #1168.  THIS PARTICULAR TANK HAS TWO DROP POINTS.  ONE OF THE DROP OFF POINTS IS USED REGULARLY WHILE THE OTHER IS SELDOM OR NEVER USED.  WHILE OUR DRIVER WAS DROPPING FUEL INTO THE BELOW GROUND TANK THE CAP A THE OTHER DROP POINT CAME OFF ALLOWING FUEL TO LEAK OUT.  APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS CAME OUT OF THIS SECOND DROP POINT.  THE STORE MANAGER AND OUR DRIVER CONTAINED AND CLEANED THE SPILL UTILIZING ABSORB ALL AND SPILL RAGS.  AFTER THE GASOLINE WAS PICKED UP, THEY SCRUBBED THE LOCATION.  THE FAULTY CAP HAS BEEN REPLACED.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: WHILE INSPECTING OUTBOUND TRAIN, LEAKAGE WAS OBSERVED ON THE SIDE OF THE TANK CAR, ACFX 89093, POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION, 8, UN1814, PG II. INSPECTION OF THE TANK CAR FITTINGS REVEALED THE FRANGIBLE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT HAD BURST.  A RAILROAD HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONDER AND BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES INSPECTOR REPLACED THE BURST FRANGIBLE DISC.  AFTER THE LEAKAGE WAS WASHED OFF, THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.
FREIGHT WAS LOADED ON SKID WHEN IT WAS LOADED.  FREIGHT WAS PUSHED INTO ANOTHER PALLET.  FROM MOVEMENT OF FREIGHT WHEN TRANSPORTED, CAN WAS CRUSHED.  SPILLED MATERIAL EVAPORATED.
DRUM WAS PUNCTURED ON THE SIDE NEAR THE BOTTOM.  IT WAS PLACED ON ITS SIDE TO PREVENT LEAKING.
UPON LOADING ONE DRUM STRUCK WITH THE TIP OF THE HI-LO BLADE CAUSING A VERY SMALL PUNCTURE.  DRUM WAS PLACED ON ITS SIDE TO PREVENT LEAKING.

column42: HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 5 PERCENT BUT LESS THAN 16 PERCENT AVAILABLE CHLORINE
column168: FORKLIFT DRIVER APPROACHED THE SKID AND PUNCTURED THE DRUM WITH THE FORKS TOO HIGH.  ASSOCIATE RETRAINED ON PROPER OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT.

UPON BREAKING THIS TRAILER, THE PAILS WERE STACKED ON FLOOR WITH A SKID IN FRONT THAT HAD RUPTURED THE PAIL.  THE PAIL AND SPILLAGE WERE CLEANED UP AND FORWARDED TO MIKE CROUSE IN LITTLE ROCK.  USE OF PROPER DUNNAGE AND BLOCKING AND BRACING WAS COVERED WITH INVOLVED PERSONNEL.
column172: Plastic pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: UPON OPENING THE TRAILER DOOR, DOCKMAN NOTICED THE SHIPMENT OF PALLETIZED BAGS HAD SLID AGAINST TRAILER DOOR WHILE IN TRANSIT.  DOCKMAN USED FORKLIFT TO RAISE DOOR AND THE BAGS WERE RIPPED AS DOOR WAS RAISED.  WHEN DOCKMAN NOTICED BAGS WERE RIPPING, HE STOPPED UNLOADING AND CONTACTED TERMINAL MANAGER.  MANAGER CALLED SHIPPER TO HAVE MSDS FXED TO SITE OF SPILL.  AFTER CONTACTING AMERICAN FREIGHTWAYS SAFETY DEPARTMENT, MANAGER WAS ADVISED TO CALL LOCAL ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP AGENCY (HERITAGE). HERITAGE ARRIVED ON SITE AND SPENT APPROXIMATELY 1 HOUR  CLEANING UP ROUGHLY 5# OF THE PRODUCT.  REMAINDER OF SHIPMENT WAS TAPED AND CONTAINED ON TRAILER,  THEN FORWARDED ON TO DESTINATION.  PROPER LOADING COVERED WITH PERSONNEL INVOLVED.
EMPTY DRUMS TURNED OVER - LEAKING OUT RESIDUE DURING TRANSIT.  ONLY A SMALL AMOUNT LEAKED.  NO FURTHER ACTION REQUIRED.  PROPER FREIGHT SECUREMENT PROCEDURES COVERED WITH PERSONNEL INVOLVED.

column168: DRUMS WERE LOADED ON WEAK LOOKING SKIDS THAT WERE NOT IN VERY GOOD SHAPE. A NAIL APPARENTLY WAS STICKING OUT ON ONE OF THE SKIDS AND WHEN LOADING, DRUMS SHIFTED, AND THE NAIL POKED IN ONE OF THE DRUMS.  DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY PUT IN A SALVAGE DRUM.  IF DRUMS ARE GOING TO BE PUT ON SKIDS, MAKE SURE THAT THE SKIDS ARE GOOD 4 WAYS.  PROPER INSPECTIONS AND PREPARATION ON LOADING AREA WAS COVERED WITH INVOLVED PERSONNEL.

column168: DRIVER DISCOVERED ONE DRUM LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM CHIME SEAM.  DRIVER OVERPACKED THE DRUM AND ABSORBED ALL SPILLED MATERIAL, PLACING IT ALSO IN THE DRUM.  ALL PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED AND ALL RESIDUE FROM THE SPILL WAS ACCEPTED FOR DISPOSAL AT THE RECEIVER.

column17: HUNT J B SPECIAL COMMODITIES I
column168: DRIVER DISCOVERED ONE DRUM LEAKING FROM AROUND TOP CLOSURE.  ONE OF THE BUNGS WOULD NOT SEAL CAUSING PRODUCT TO SEEP OUT ONTO THE TOP OF THE DRUM. DRIVER ABSORBED ALL SPILLED MATERIAL AND USED CAULKING TO SECURE THE BUNG CLOSURE.  ALL WASTE MATERIAL WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE RECEIVER AND ACCEPTED BY SAME.

column17: HUNT J B SPECIAL COMMODITIES I
column168: DRIVER DISCOVERED BOTH BUNGS ON ONE DRUM WERE LOOSE RESULTING IN SPILLAGE ON THE TOP OF THE DRUM AND ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO TIGHTEN THE BUNG CLOSURES AND ABSORB ALL SPILLAGE USING ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE ABSORBANT MATERIAL WAS PICKED UP FOR DISPOSAL AT THE RECEIVING FACILITY.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE RECEIVER, THE TRAILER WILL BE TESTED TO DETERMINE THE LEVEL OF CONTAMINATION AND THEN DECONTAMINATED TO A LEVEL BELOW 10 PARTS PER MILLION.  ALL SPILL RESIDUE WILL BE DISPOSED BY THE RECEIVER.

THE UNIT WAS TRAVELING WESTBOUND ON HIGHWAY 225 WHEN THE RUPTURE DISC (A PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE) BLEW.  THIS PRODUCT BUILDS PRESSURE, NORMALLY ABOUT 10 TO 15 PSI, WHILE BEING TRANSPORTED.  THE RUPTURE DISC IS RATED AT 45 PSI AND SHOULD NOT HAVE BLOWN.  WE ARE CHECKING THE DISC FOR DEFECTS AND WILL CONTACT THE MANUFACTURER FOR ASSISTANCE.
THE SEAL ON THE PUMP IS LEAKING.  WILL HAVE SEAL REPAIRED BEFORE FINISHING THE UNLOADING.

column42: ALKYLAMINES, N.O.S. OR POLYALKYLAMINES, N.O.S. CORROSIVE
column168: CUSTOMER TANK INSIDE BUILDING.  DRIVER CANNOT SEE TANK.  DRIVER HAD ALREADY SHUTDOWN, AND PRODUCT STARTED TO FAOM OVER.  TANK WAS IN A CONTAINED AREA, AND PRODUCT WAS WASHED BACK INTO SYSTEM.
THE PACKING AND THE PUMP WERE LEAKING.  CLEANED UP WITH A RAG.  ONLY A COUPLE OF DROPS LEAKED.

WHILE UNLOADING PALLET FROM TRAILER, ONE CARTON FELL, AND ALL FOUR BOTTLES BURST.  LOST FOUR GALLONS.  CONTENT WAS ABSORBED WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACE INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM ALONG WITH DAMAGED CONTAINER.
DOCKMAN DISCOVERED ONE SMALL CARTON (1 POUND) WET WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER. UPON INSPECTION, CONTAINER WAS FOUND EMPTY, BUT NO DAMAGE WAS NOTED.

THE BOTTOM OF A PALLET PUNCTURED ONE BOX CONTAINING THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  BAKING SODA WAS USED TO CLEAN UP THE SMALL AMOUNT LOST, AND THE CONTAINER WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY CONTAINER.  DOCKMEN WERE INSTRUCTED TO USE MORE CARE WHEN LOADING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: WHILE DRIVER WAS PARKED, WITH SAFETY CONES PROPERLY POSITIONED UNLOADING UNLEADED GASOLINE, A WOMAN DROVE INTO THE GAS STATION.  TO GET TO THE PUMPS, SHE SAY THE DRIER UNLOADING, THE TRANSPORT IN ITS PARKED POSITION, THE HOSE CONNECTED TO THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK, AND HAD TO MANEUVER CAR AROUND THE POSITIONED SAFETY CONES.  AFTER FILLING HER CAR WITH GASOLINE, SHE BACKED UP AND OVER A SAFETY CONE AND STRUC THE DOWNSPOUT. THE COLLISION CAUSED THE 4-INCH EVERTIGHT DOWNSPOUT TO BREAK AND TO BEND THE 4-INCH UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK FILL PIPE.  THE TRANSPORT DRIVER CONTAINED THE SPILL ON CONCRETE USING A SPILL KIT AND TWO BAGS OF CAT LITTER.  THE CLEAN UP WAS IMMEDIATE AND APPRPOVED BY THE WEBSTER WISCONSIN FIRE DEPARTMENT AS A GOOD JOB.  CLEAN UP MATERIALS WERE DISPOSED OF AS PER WISCONSIN REGULATIONS.

DRIVER ARRIVED EARLY TO UNLOAD.  WENT TO SLEEP.  CUSTOMER WOKE HIM WHEN READY TO UNLOAD.  DRIVER BEGAN MOVING VEHICLE.  CUT RIGHT HAND SHORT. STRUCK YELLOW POLE AT ENTRANCE OF UNLOADING FACILITY WHICH CAUSED AND CRACKED LOADING HEADS.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: DRIVER STARTED TO PUMP OFF-LOAD AND NOTICED PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM AROUND THE PUMP SHAFT.  HE SHUT DOWN THE OFF-LOADING OPERATION, PUT A BUCKET UNDER THE PUMP AND TIGHTENED THE PUMP PACKING.  RESTARTED AND OFF-LOADED THE REMAINDER OF THE LOAD.  CONSIGNEE PUT OIL DRY ON THE SPILL, CLEANED UP, AND WILL DISPOSE OF PROPERLY.

DRIVER, ATTEMPTING TO TIGHTEN THE FITTING ON THE PRODUCT PUMP, CLOSED UNLOADING VALVES, AND WHEN HE DISCONNECTED THE DISCHARGE HOSE, HE WAS SPLASHED WITH PRODUCT IN THE FACE AND CHEST.  HE USED THE EYEWASH AT THE CONSIGNEE, AND THEY CALLED THE AMBULANCE AND TRANSPORTED HIM TO THE HOSPITAL FOR CHECKING.  HE WAS CHECKED AND RELEASED.  THE PRODUCT THAT WENT ONTO THE CONCRETE UNLOADING PAD EVAPORATED BEFORE THEY COULD CLEAN IT UP.
PACKAGE WAS UNLOADED WITH LEAKAGE NOTED.  EXAMINATION OF THE PLASTIC DRUM REVEALED A PUNCTURE ON THE BOTTOM.  THE LEAKAGE WAS CONTAINED.  PACKAGE WAS REPACKED FOR RETURN TO SHIPPER.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: THE TRACTOR SEMI-CARGO TANK TRAILER WAS PARKED ON PRIVATE PROPERTY IN THE PROCESS OF UNLOADING GASOLINE INTO THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK OF THE SERVICE STATION.  THE DRIVER OF A PASSENGER MOTOR VEHICLE STRUCK THE UNLOADING HOSE AND FITTING, CAUSING THE FITTING TO DISCONNECT FROM THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK CONNECTION.  THE DRIVER OF THE TRACTOR SEMI-CARGO TANK TRAILER IMMEDIATELY CLOSED THE COMPARTMENT VALVE AND THE INTERNAL VALVES, PREVENTING ADDITIONAL QUANTITY OF GASOLINE TO BE RELEASED.  THE DRIVER OF THE PASSENGER MOTOR VEHICLE LEFT THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT.  HE WAS ALLEGED TO BE UNDER THE INFLUENCE.  THE DRIVER OF THE TRACTOR SEMI-CARGO TANK TRAILER OBTAINED CAT LITTER FROM THE STORE AND SPREAD IT OVER THE AREA.  A SMALL QUANTITY OF THE GASOLINE REACHED A GRATED OPEN STORM DRAIN ALONG THE CURB LINE BEFORE THE DRIVER COULD CONTAIN THE RELEASE.  POST ACCIDENT INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT THE ACCIDENT WAS NON-PREVENTABLE ON THE PART OF THE DRIVER OF THE TRACTOR SEMI-CARGO TANK VEHICLE.  THE GLOBE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE GLOBE POLICE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE SCENE IMMEDIATELY AND ASSUMED CONTROL OF THE SCENE.

THE STATION PERSONNEL THAT HAD STUCK THE TANK THE NIGHT BEFORE HAD USED THE WRONG COVER AND THEN LEFT THE CAP OFF.  THE CAP SHOULD HAVE BEEN ACTUALLY A PERMANENT CAP FOR THAT END OF TRAILER.  ERICKSON OIL MAINTENANCE WAS CALLED AND PROBLEM WAS DEALT WITH.  A PADLOCK WAS PUT ON UNUSED CAPS UNTIL PERMANENTLY SEALED CAPS ARE INSTALLED.

WE WERE UNLOADING A TRUCKLOAD OF FUEL OIL INTO OUR CUSTOMER'S BULK PLANT. THE CUSTOMER'S HOSE WAS CONNECTED BETWEEN OUR TRUCK UNLOADING PUMP AND THE CUSTOMERS BULK PLANT PIPE.  SHORTLY AFTER WE BEGAN PUMPING A PINHOLE DEVELOPED IN THE CUSTOMER'S HOSE AND FUEL OIL SPRAYED OUT.  OUR DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF OUR TRUCK PUMP, DRAINED OUT THE DEFECTIVE HOSE AND OBTAINED A REPLACEMENT HOSE TO FINISH UNLOADING OUR TRAILER.
A 275 GALLON STATIONARY STEEL TANK FELL OVER DUE TO UNKNOWN CAUSE. PRODUCT LEAKED OUT THE FILL CAP.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS ENROUTE TO HIS DESTINATION.  HE HAD STOPPED AT A TRAFFIC LIGHT.  AS HE PROCEEDED FORWARD THE LIQUID CARGO SURGED AND THE RUPTURE DISC IN THE REAR CLEANOUT CAP FRACTURED ALLOWING PRODUCT TO ESCAPE.  THE PRODUCT WENT ONTO THE ROADWAY AND ALSO SPRAYED A CAR TRAVELING NEXT TO OUR VEHICLE.  TH AUTHORITIES WERE CALLED AND HANDLED THE CLEAN UP.  THE RUPTURE DISC WAS REPLACED AND THE UNIT CONTINUED TO ITS DESTINATION.

OUR DRIVER WAS ENROUTE TO HIS DESTINATION WHEN STOPPED AT A REST AREA FOR A BREAK.  HE WAS DOING A WALK AROUND OF HIS UNIT WHEN HE DISCOVERED MATERIAL DRIPPING FROM THE STEAM COILS OF HIS TRAILER.  HE PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE LEAK TO CONTAIN THE MATERIAL AND NOTIFIED THE COMPANY AND THE AUTHORITIES.  ANOTHER TRAILER WAS DISPATCHED ALONG WITH A RESPONSE CREW TO TRANSFER THE CARGO.  A CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR WAS ENGAGED TO CLEAN UP THE AREA AT THE DIRECTION OF THE ALABAMA DEPT.  OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT. THE LEAKING TRAILER WAS REMOVED FROM SERVICE FOR INSPECTION AND REPAIR.

OUR DRIVER RETURNED A PORTION OF HIS CARGO TO THE TERMINAL SINCE THE CONSIGNEE COULD NOT ACCEPT THE ENTIRE AMOUNT SHIPPED.  AS HE WAS DOING HIS TRIP HE NOTED A SLIGHT DRIP OF PRODUCT FROM THE REAR PRODUCT VALVE WAS REPAIRED AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  THE SPILL AREA WAS CLEANED UP BY OUR EMPLOYEE.

MATERIAL STARTED DRIPPING AS DRUM WAS TRANSPORTED FROM ELEVATOR TO TAILGATE OF TRUCK.  DRUM STARTED LEAKING WORSE AS IT WAS PLACED IN THE TRUCK. ABOUT 1/2 CUP LEAKED OUT OF TRUCK BEFORE THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED. ABSORBANT SHEETS & LOOSE ABSORBANT WAS PLACED AND DOWN HILL SIDE OF DRUM TO CONTAIN SPILL.  MATERIAL IN DRUM WAS TRANSFERRED TO NEW DRUM.  EXCESS LIQUID WAS WIPED UP WITH ABSORBANT TOWELS AND AREA WAS SWEEPED CLEAN, INCLUDING MATERIAL ON ASPHAT AND REAR OF TRUCK.  SPILL CATCH BASIN WAS EMPTIED INTO NEW DRUM.  IN THE FUTURE, DRUMS WILL BE MORE CLOSELY INSPECTED BEFORE BEING MOVED.

THE TRUCK STRUCK A CEMENT DIVIDER WALL BETWEEN THE NORTH AND SOUTH BOUND LANES.  THE TRUCK OVER TURNED COMING TO A STOP IN THE NORTH BOUND LANES AGAINST AND ON THE CEMENT DIVIDER STILL HEADED SOUTH. LOCAL OFFICIALS CLOSED I-95 FROM 1:30 EST TO 19:00 EST DUE  TO THE POSSIBILITY OF PRODUCT LOSS AND TO PROTECT EMERGENCY WORKERS.  HIGHWAY CLOSING IS REASON FOR REPORT

AT APPROXIMATELY 2:15 AM KEVIN BRASWELL NOTIFIED ME OF A LEAKING PACKAGE HE HAD DISCOVERED ON THE SOUTH SLIDE.  I DISCOVERED IT TO A CORROSIVE FROM VISIBLE MARKINGS ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE BOX.  WHILE WEARING THE APPROPRIATE PPE, I NEUTRALIZED THE SPILL WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE.  THIS TOOK ABOUT 20 MINUTES.  AFTER THAT WAS DONE, I TOOK A PH TEST AND IT CAME UP TO BE NEUTRAL.  I THEN CLEANED OFF THE SLIDE, THE ENTIRE CLEAN UP PROCEDURE WAS DONE.  ACCORDING TO THE RESPONSE SHEETS AND THE DECISION, THE BOTTLE WAS REBOXED AND SHIPPED BACK.  WHILE THE CONTAINER UASDS POSTED.

column168: A WET PACKAGE CAME DOWN THE CHUTE ONTO THE ROLLERS AT DR 139.  PSC KATHY PIRRWITZ WAS SUMMONED AND WEARING PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT REMOVED IF TO A PROCESSING AREA.  UPON INSPECTION SHE FOUND THE NECT NEAR THE LID WAS DENTED.  THE CONTENTS WERE PUT IN A NEW CONTAINERS, REBOXED AND RTS'D. THE CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND DISPOSED OF USING PROPER DAMAGE PACKAGE PROCESSING PROCEDURES.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER WAS GOING FROM BRISTOL TO GAFFNEY AND CAR APPROACH DRIVER IN MIDDLE OF ROAD AND DRIVER WENT OFF SHOULDER AND BACK TRAILER FLIPPED OVER.  THE 3 CARDBOARD DRUMS WITH SUBSTANCE INSIDE OVERTURNED AND VERY LITTLE WAS LOST. EASTMAN HAZMAT WAS BROUGHT ONTO THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT.

WAREHOUSEMAN, WAS OFF LOADING SOME OTHER MATERIAL ON THE TRAILER THAT WAS TOPPED ON THIS PALLET, AND IN SO DOING THE FORK BLADE CUT ONE OF THE TOP CARTONS SLICING OPEN THE PLASTIC JUG, MOST OF THE LOSS CONTENTS WAS TAKEN BY THE CARTONS UNDER THE ONE DAMAGED.

THIS PIECE FAILED DUE TO METAL FATIGUE.  UPON UNLOADING THE TRAILER, THIS PAIL WAS SITTING ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THERE WAS CARDBOARD ON TOP OF THE PAIL.  THE TOP SEAM HAD FAILED AND THE LIQUD LEAKED INTO THE CARDBOARD. THE CARDBOARD HAD SOAKED UP ALL OF THE LIQUID.  THERE WAS REALLY NOTHING OVERNITE COULD HAVE DONE TO PREVENT THIS, AS THIS WAS PROBABLY A SHIPPER LOAD AND COUNT AND THE ORIGIN TERMINAL PROBABLY NEVER SAW THE FREIGHT.

column62: Dropped; Dropped; Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS IN THE PROCESS OF TAKING A SKID OF FREIGHT OFF THE INBOUND TRAILER.  THE SKID CONTAINING THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL HAD BEEN LOADED ON TOP OF ANOTHER SKID WHICH WAS BEHIND THE SKID OF FREIGHT BEING TAKEN OFF.  WHEN THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR PULLED THE SKID BACK THE SKID OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FELL FORWARD.  THE CARTONS FELL TO THE TRAILER FLOOR WITH THE IMPACT BREAKING THE PLASTIC CAPS OF SEVEN BOTTLES THEREBY RELEASING THE CONTENTS.  CARTONS TRANSFERRED TO OS&D FOR FURTHER HANDLING. THE SKID CONTAINING THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHOULD NOT HAVE BEEN LOADED ON TOP OF ANOTHER SKID IN THE TRAILER AT THE ORIGIN TERMINAL.  THE FREIGHT SHOULD BEEN LOADED ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.

WHEN TRAILER WAS UNLOADED, CARTON WAS WET.  LID OR CAP ON ONE JUG WAS LOOSE.  SMALL AMOUNT LEAKED OUT AND WET EXTERNAL CARTON.  CONSIGNEE REFUSED AS COULD NOT SELL IN THE DIRTY CARTON.  NO DAMAGE TO OTHER FREIGHT.  LID WAS RETIGHTENED AND SHIPPER SAID TO RETURN TO THEM.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: I WAS UNAWARE OF ANY PROBLESM UNTIL DRIVER RETURNED WITH DR & PHOTO OF DRUM.  THEN THE NEXT DAY, CONSIGNEE CALLS & SAID THAT MATERIAL WAS CONTAMINATED & COULD NOT USE.  HE IS PLANNING OF FILING CLAIM.  WE RECEIVED DISPOSITION TO RETURN DAMAGED MERCHANDISE TO SHIPPER IN A SALVAGE DRUM.  RETURNING FOR CREDIT AGAINST CLAIM.  WE MUST STRESS HOW IMPORTANT IT IS TO HANDLE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WITH PROPER HANDLING PROCEDURES.  TO ENSURE THIS DOES NOT HAPPEN AGAIN.

column62: Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: ON 10/13 06300 BACKED IN INBOUND RIC MISC TRL OPEN THE DOOR FOUND 1 DRUM TURNED OVER ON IT'S SIDE, IT HAD BEEN ROLLING AROUND ON THE FLOOR.  THIS CAUSED THE BUNG SCREW CAPS TO WORK LOOSE AND STARTED TO SEEP.  ABOUT A PINT LEAKED ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  CALLED CHEMTREC THEY SAID TO USE BAKING SODA TO NEUTRALIZE THE ACID, AND THEY FAXED OVER M.S.D.S. FOR SULFURIC ACID.  THE CONSIGNEE AGREED TO TAKE THE DRUM.

DOCK MAN WAS IN THE PROCEESS OF UNLOADING FREIGHT OFF INBOUND TRAILER WHEN THE PAIL HE WAS HANDLING SLIPPED FROM HIS HAND AND STRUCK SOME OTHER FREIGHT.  IMPACT CAUSED A SMALL PUNCTURE ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE METAL PAIL.  PAIL TRANSFERRED TO OS&D FOR FURTHER HANDLING.  DOCK PERSONNEL SHOULD ENSURE THAT THEY HAVE A FIRM GRIP ON PAIL HANDLES WHEN THEY ARE BEING HANDLED.

DOCK MAN WAS UNLOADING FRIGHT FROM IN BOUND TRAILER WHEN HE NOTICED THAT ONE OF THE METAL PAILS WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM.  APPARENTLY DURING TRANSIT THE CONSTANT VIBRATION OF THE TRAILER FLOOR AGAINST THE BOTTOM OF THE METAL PAIL CAUSED 2 INCH CRACK ON THE BOTTOM.  PAIL TRANSFERRED TO OS&D FOR FURTHER HANDLING.  DOCK PERSONNEL SHOULD PLACE CARDBOARD DUNNAGE ON TRAILER FLOOR BEFORE LOADING METAL PAILS ON TRAILERS.

column168: DRIVER WAS MAKING DELIVERY TO CUSTOMER WHEN IT WAS NOTICED THAT THE BOTTOMS OF TWO OF THE CARTONS WERE WET.  AT THAT POINT THE CUSTOMER REFUSED DELIVERY OF THE FREIGHT AND THE DRIVER BROUGHT IT BACK TO THE TERMINAL.  FREIGHT WAS TRANSFERRED TO OS&D FOR INSPECTION.  THE CARTONS WERE OPENED AND IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT TWO CLOSURE CAPS WERE LOOSE ON TWO CONTAINERS.  CAPS WERE RETIGHTENED.  FREIGHT HELD IN OS&D AWAITING DISPOSITION FROM SHIPPER.  SHIPPER SHOULD ENSURE THAT CAPS ARE SECURE ON CONTAINERS BEFORE BEING OFFERED FOR SHIPMENT.

DOCK MAN WAS UNLOADING FREIGHT FROM TRAILER WHEN HE DISCOVERED THE DAMAGED CARTON.  THE CARTON WAS FOUND WEDGED BETWEEN TWO PALLETS OF OTHER FREIGHT. THE WEDGING ACTION OF THE TWO PALLETS IN TRANSIT MASHED AND PUNCTURED THE CARTON AND PUNCTURED ONE OF THE PLASTIC BOTTLES INSIDE THE CARTON.  CARTON TRANSFERRED TO OS&D FOR FURTHER HANDLING.  FREIGHT LOADERS NEED TO EXERCISE GOOD JUDGEMENT WHEN PLACING CARTONS ON TRAILERS TO MINIMIZE DAMAGE FROM OTHER FREIGHT.

column168: TANK CAR BEING SWITCHED AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN GRAND RAPIDS, MICHIGAN, WAS OBSERVED TO SLOSH PRODUCT FROM THE TOP WHEN MOVED.  TRAIN MASTER BERNARD INSPECTED CAR AND REPORTED LEAKAGE WAS COMING FROM AROUND THE MANWAY.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED ON THE "SCALE TRACK", AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED THROUGH CHEMTREC.  THE SHIPPER REQUESTED ASSISTANCE FROM DOW CHEMICAL AT MIDLAND, MICHIGAN.  DOW RESPONDED A TEAM TO GRAND RAPIDS, AND THEY RESPLACED A BAD MANWAY COVER GASKET ON THE TANK CAR.  THE CAR WAS SECURED AND RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION AT 20:30 ON 10/22/94.

SWITCH CREW AT CSTX RAIL YARD AT RIVERDALE, ILLNOIS, OBSERVED PRODUCT SLOSH FROM TOP OF A TANK CAR WHEN THE CAR WAS MOVED.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED, AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED THROUGH CHEMTREC.  THE SHIPPER ARRANGED FOR RESCAR TO RESPOND AND MAKE REPAIRS.  RESCAR RESPONDED AND FOUND LEAK HAD OCCURRED FROM THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE.  APPEARS "O"-RING IN VALVE WAS BAD AND ALLOWED PRODUCT TO SLOSH OUT.  RESCAR REPLACED THE O-RING.  THEY ALSO CHECKED THE MANWAY AND THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE:  BOTH WERE IN PROPER CONDITION AND SECURED.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED AT ABOUT 21:30.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: A PALLET WITH 2 DRUMS WAS SITTING IN BAY, DRIVER ON FORKLIFT #1 WAS GOING TO TURN PALLET AROUND SO THAT DRIVER ON FORKLIFT #2 COULD GET UNDER PLT TO LOAD ON TRAILER. WHEN FORKLIFT DRIVER #1 TURNED PALLET HE ACCIDENTALLY STUCK FORK INTO DRUM AND DIDN'T KNOWN IT UNTIL FORKLIFT DRIVER #2 BACKED UP WITH PLT. AT THAT TIME FORKLIFT DRIVER #1 TOLD #2 THAT THE DRUM WAS LEAKING PAINT AND TO GET IT OFF THE DOCK. DRIVER #2 WENT ALL THE WAY AROUND THE DOCK TO GET THE PAINT OUT OF WORK AREA. THE SPILLED PAINT WAS CLEANED UP BY PUTTING OIL DRI ON IT AND THEN SCOOPING IT UP WHEN IT WAS DRY. THE DOCKMEN ON THE FORKLIFTS WERE TOLD TO BE MORE CAREFUL WHEN TRYING TO TURN A PALLET WITH A FORKLIFT AND TO STOP WHERE THEY ARE WHEN THEY SEE A LEAK AND TURN THE DRUM UPSIDE DOWN IF THE PUNCTURE IS ON THE BOTTOM OF DRUM UNTIL A RECOVERY DRUM CAN BE GOTTEN AND DRUM CAN BE PUT IN IT.

TRAILER CAME IN FROM P/D AND WAS BEING UNLOADED AT THE DOCK. AS THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING UNLOADED, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A SMALL LEAK WAS ON A DRUM ATTACHMENT ON A FORKLIFT. THE DRUM WAS SEALED OFF AND TAKEN TO THE OS&D BAY FOR LATER DISPOSITION.

DRIVER HAD OFF LOADED APPROXIMATELY 2,450 GALLONS INTO STORAGE TANK. CONSIGNEE HAD DRIVER SHUT DOWN AND MOVE UNIT FOR DRUMMING OFF THE REST OF THE LOAD. THEY GOT HOOKED UP FOR DRUMMING AND TOLD THE DRIVER TO START PUMP AND HE DID SO. HE GOT OUT OF THE TRACTOR, WALKED AROUND THE FRONT OF THE UNIT WHEN THE UNLOADER SHUT OFF THE DRUMMING NOZZLE WHICH CAUSED THE UNLOADING HOSE TO BURST APPROXIMATELY 3 FEET FROM DRUMMING NOZZLE. THE UNLOADER, MR. CHARLES RUSHING, GOT SOME PRODUCT SPLASHED IN HIS EYES. HE WENT TO THE INDUSTRIAL CLINIC, HAD HIS EYES FLUSHED OUT AND RETURNED TO FINISH DRUM AND WILL DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.

CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETED WITH DEPT. OF ECOLOGY APPROVING. CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS HAULED TO BUSCH DIST PLANT, PUT ON VISQUEEN AND WILL BE FARMED. NARROW SHOULDER AND DRIVER ERROR WAS RESPONSIBLY.

APPROXIMATELY FIVE TO TEN GALLONS OF DENATURED ALCOHOL WAS SPILLED ON 10/26/96 AT CSI MIDWEST TERMINAL IN COLUMBUS, OHIO DURING UNLOAD PREPARATIONS.  DRIVER OF CARGO VEHICLE REPORTED THAT HE WAS ENROUTE TO THE DELIVERY LOCATION ON INTERSTATE I-70.  AT ABOUT 0700, HE EXITED THE INTERSTATE AT EXIT #10 IN OHIO INTO A ROAD SIDE TRUCK STOP.  DRIVER CONDUCTED A DOT REQUIRED SAFETY CHECK OF THE VEHICLE AND ASSERTS THAT THE VEHICLE WAS IN GOD CONDITION AND DID NOT NOTE ANY REMARKABLE COMPLICATION. AFTER HIS INSPECTION, THE DRIVER LEFT THE VEHICLE UNATTENDED WHEN HE ENTERED THE TRUCK STOP FACILITY FOR A BRIEF PERIOD OF TIME LESS THAN FIFTEEN MINUTES.  THE DRIVER LEFT THE FACILITY AND CLIMBED BACK INTO THE TRUCK WITHOUT MAKING A WALK AROUND OF THE VEHICLE.  THE VEHICLE LEFT THE TRUCK STOP AND CONTINUED TO THE UNLOAD DESTINATION.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE UNLOAD DESTINATION, THE DRIVER REPORTED THAT HE POSITIONED THE VEHICLE FOR UNLOADING.   IN PREPARATION FOR UNLOADING, THE DRIVER FIRST OPENED THE CARGO TANK SAFETY VALVE THAT WAS LOCATED IN THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER.  THE DRIVER STATED THAT HE BEGAN SPILLING FROM THE SIDE PRODUCT PIPE.  HE IMMEDIATELY SHUT THE PRODUCT VALVE OFF.  APPROXIMATELY FIVE TO TEN GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS SPILLED.  A CUSTOMER EMPLOYEE CLEANED THE SPILL AREA WITH WATER AND THE RESIDUE WAS WASHED DOWN A SEWER DRAIN.  APPARENTLY, AN UNAUTHORIZED PERSON OPENED THE TRAILER'S PRODUCT VALVE AND PIPE CAP DURING THE PERIOD THAT THE DRIVER WAS INSIDE THE TRUCK STOP FACILITY.

column168: GATEWAY WESTERN INTERMODAL TRAIN #283, TRAVELING AT APPROXIMATELY 25 MPH, WAS PULLING THROUGH THE LENOX INTERLOCKING AT MITCHELL, ILLINOIS, SOUTH OF OLD ALTON RAOD, WHEN TRAILER SBDZ 231953 FELL OFF INTERMODAL FLAT TTOX 135185.  INVESTIGATION BY THE EMPLOYEES OF GATEWAY'S MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT, PACIFIC RAIL CORPORATION, AND TTX COMPANY DETERMINED THE STANCHION WAS NOT IN THE LOCKED POSITION, ALLOWING THE TRAILER TO FALL FROM CAR.  TTOX 135185 DERAILED AS A RESULT OF THE TRAILER FALLING AND WAS PULLED APPROXIMATELY ONE HALF MILE WHEN A FROG AND SWITCH AT NORTH LENOX STATION CAUSED TRAILING CARS TO DERAIL AND OVERTURN.  SBDZ 231953, CONTAINING TWENTY 55-GALLON DRUMS OF ETHYL LACTATE, 6 GALLONS RED PRIMER AND 8 GALLONS OF YELLOW ENAMEL, TURNED OVER.  ONE DRUM OF ETHYL LACTATE LEAKED APPROXIMATELY THREE GALLONS THROUGH THE TOP OF THE DRUM, THREE CANS OF THE YELLOW ENAMEL OPENED, AND APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS WERE LOST.

THIS MATERIAL WAS ON A PALLET THAT WAS LOADED IN A FULL TRAILER OF MISCELLANEOUS FREIGHT. OUR DRIVER SUFFERED A MINOR BURN ON HIS RIGHT FOREARM WHILE HE WAS UNHOOKING THE HOSES. OUR INVESTIGATION TO DATE HAS REVEALED THAT THE TANK WE WERE PUMPING INTO WAS OVERFILLED AND THE RESULTING FUMES WERE IGNITED BY A SPARK OF UNKNOWN ORIGIN. column168: A BULK TRUCK WITH SEPARATE CARGO TANKS OF EMULSION (BLASTING AGENT), AMMONIUM NITRATE AND FUEL OIL SLID INTO A DITCH WHILE BACKING-UP ON A NARROW ROAD ON COMPAY PROPERTY. WHILE ATTEMPTING TO STABILIZE THE TRUCK, IT SLOWLY ROLLED ONTO ITS SIDE SPILLING APPROXIMATELY 3000 POUNDS OF AMMONIUM NITRATE FROM THE CARGO HATCH. AFTER THE TRUCK WAS RECOVERED, APPROXIMATELY 400 POUNDS OF AMMONIUM NITRATE WAS NOT RECOVERED FROM THE TALL GRASS AND BUSHES IN THE AREA. NO OTHER PRODUCT WAS SPILLED.

column168: OUR LOGEX DRIVER WAS ENROUTE TO FT. IRWIN, CA ON FT. IRWIN RD. THIS ROAD IS NOT HEAVILY TRAVELLED AND IS VERY DARK DUE TO LACK OF STREET LIGHTS. THE DRIVER WAS ABOUT 10 MILES OFF THE FREEWAY WHEN AN AUTOMOBILE APPROACHED HIM FROM THE REAR. THE AUTOMOBILE LIGHTS ILLUMINATED THE REAR OF OUR TRAILER AND THE DRIVER NOTICED A VAPOR CLOUD. THE DRIVER PULLED OFF THE HIGHWAY AS SOON AS IT WAS SAFE TO DO SO AND FOUND LIQUID NITROGEN LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE FILL VALVE. THE BOTTOM FILL PACKING NUT LOOSENED, ALLOWING THE HAND VALVE TO VIBRATE OPEN. OUR DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO CLOSE THE HAND VALVE DUE TO THE LIQUID COMING OUT OF THE VALVE. THE DRIVER POSITIONED THE REAR OF THE CARGO TANK TOWARD THE DESERT IN ORDER TO KEEP THE LIQUID OFF THE HIGHWAY. THE LIQUID NITROGEN DISSAPATED AS IT HIT THE GROUND. THE TRAILER WAS THROUGHLY INSPECTED UPON RETURN TO THE TERMINAL, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE PACKING NUT HAD WORKED LOOSE AND THE HAND VALVE VIBRATED OPEN.

LESS THAN ONE CUP OF MATERIAL HAD LEAKED ONTO STEEL SECONDARY CONTAINMENT PAN WITH NO MATERIAL RELEASED INTO THE ENVIRONMENT. T/C GATX 40093 WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING AT NASHVIULLE FROM ITS BOTTOM VALVE.  SHIPPER, Q O CHEMICAL INC, WAS CONTACTED (BROMAN CUMPTON: 901-324-8851).  SHIPPER HAD FERGUSON HARBORS TIGHTEN BOTTOM VALVE ELBOW. CAR SECURED AND RESEASED.

TANK CAR REPORTED VENTING VAPORS AT THE CAR SHOP IN CSX TRANSPORTAION'S RAIL YARD AT RIVERDALE, IL.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC AND ARRANGED FOR RESCAR TO RESPOND TO MAKE REPAIRS.  RESCAR FOUND THAT THE LIQUID EDUCTION VALVE WAS OPEN, AND THIS FLUID PHLANGE COVERING THE VALVE WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED.  RESCAR CLOSD THE VALVE AND TIGHTENED PHLANGE DOWN, STOPPING THE VAPOR RELEASE.  THE CAR WAS SECURED AT ABOUT 121:OO.

TANK CAR ACFX 77591 WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM ITS TOP.  CAR ISOLATED. SHIPPER CONTACTED, KEN WILEY: 904-571-3062, AND WILL REPAIR AND FIX CAR. SHIPPER CONTRACTED FRITT RAILCAR, WHO REPLACED THE RUPTURE DISC.

UPON OUTBOUND INSPECTION OF TRAIN Q40012, HAZMAT MANAGER FOUND GATX 41074 WITH EVIDENCE OF LADING SPILLAGE.  CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT RUPTURE DISK HAD BURST.  A NEW RUPTURE DISK WAS PLACED IN SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY. CAR WAS SECURED AND SENT ONTO DESTINATION.

TANK CAR GATX 13500 WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM ITS TOP AT BIRMINGHAM, AL.  SHIPPER, HOLNAM, INC., WAS CONTACTED.  HOLNAM CONTACTED TRANSPORT SERVICES TO DO REPAIRS.  TRANSPORT SERVICES PLACED A NEW GASKET IN MANWAY. CAR SECURED AND RELEASED.

TWO ROAD DRIVERS NOTICED ODOR.  CALLED TERMINAL MANAGER.  MANAGER CAME TO OVERNITE TERMINAL TO CONFIRM THAT THERE WAS A HAZMAT INCIDENT.  CALLED AND ADVISED SAFETY DEPARTMANTE AND WASTE SERVICES TO CLEANUP AND CHECK OUT TANK/CANISTER.  FITTING/VALVE WAS DEFECTIVE AND STARTED LEAKING IN TRANSIT.  SHIPMENT WAS MOVED TO DESTINATION AFTER VALVE REPLACED/REPAIRED.

AN MSDS WAS FAXED TO THE FED EX STATION. IT TOO CONFIRMS THAT THE MATERIALS REGULATED.  I NOTIFIED THE LAX CASFO, RHONDA HATMAKER, SPECIFICALLY, AND ADVISED THAT WE HAD WHAT WE BELIEVED TO BE AN UNDECLARED HAZ MAT.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, OR SHIPPING PAPERS TO INDICATE THE MATERIAL WAS REGULATED.  THE SHIPPER HAS BEEN NOTIFIED THAT THE FREIGHT WAS HELD FOR THE FAA. column168: THE METAL CANS DID NOT HAVE CAN CLIPS.  THE FREIGHT WAS TRUCKED FROM THE ORIGIN TO MEMPHIS WHERE IT WAS BURIED IN A ULD.  THAT ULD WAS STAGED AND ULTIMATELY PUT ON FEDEX FLT 466.  DURING THE MEM-ABQ LEG, THE UNSECURED LIDS POPPED OFF THE CANS AND SPILLED SOME OF THEIR CONTENTS.  IT WAS AT THE FEDEX ABQ STATION THAT WE WERE UNLOADING THE FREIGHT.  A CARGO HANDLER WAS OVERCOME BY FUMES FROM THE MATERIAL.  HE VOMITED AND WAS EVACUATED FROM THE BLDG.  THE INTRODUCTION OF FRESH AIR TO HIS SYSTEM CLEARED UP ALL SYMPTOMS.  HE CHOSE NOT TO SEEK MEDICAL ASSISTANCE.  HE WAS SENT HOME AT THE END OF HIS SHIFT.  REPORTED TO WORK THE NEXT DAY.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, OR SHIPPING PAPERS TO INDICATED THE SUBSTANCE WAS REGULATED.  THE MSDS SHOWS THE FLASHPOINT AS 82%F THE SHIPPER:FAA WERE CALLED.

THERE WAS A HANDLE ON THE DRUM THAT HAD AN APPARENT DEFECT ON HOW IT WAS SECURED TO THE DRUM.  THERE WAS A HOLE NEXT TO THE HANDLE ENABLING THE MATERIAL TO ESCAPE.  BAKING SODA WAS USED TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPILLED MATERIAL.  THE DRUM WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER AT THEIR REQUEST.

THREE APPEARED TO BE A DEFECTIVE FITTING ON THE DRUM.  THE POWDER ESCAPED FROM THE TOP OF THE DRUM AND THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX.  THE POWDER WAS SWEPT UP & THE BOX WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM.  THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE RECIPIENT PER THE SHIPPER.

THE SHIPPER & THE FAA HAVE BEEN NOTIFIED.  THE FREIGHT HAS BEEN HELD PENDING DISPOSITION BY THE FAA.

HOSTLER NOTICED TRAILER LEAKING IN YARD. WITH PAPERWORK WE IDENTIFIED THE MATERIAL. CALLED LAIDLAW INC. TO INVISTIGATE SPILL. WHAT HAPPENED WAS SOME ALUMIUM PIPE WAS YPUSHED BY A FORK AND PUNCTURED THE PLASTIC 55 GALLON DRUM. IN THE FUTURE THE LOADING TERMINAL WILL PUT PLYWOOD BEHIND DRUMS.

DRIVER WAS OFFLOADINF USING AIR PRESSURE. APPROXIMATELY HALF WAY THROUGH UNLOADING PROCESS NOTICED PRODUCT SEEPING FROM A HOLE IN BOTTOM OF TRAILER. SHORTLY AFTER OBSERVED THAT TANK HAD DEVELOPED A SMALL PINHOLE AND WAS SPRAYING PRODUCT IN A SMALL STREAM FROM THE HOLE. SHUT DOWN UNLOADING AND STARTED VENTING PRESSURE OFF TANK. RESPONSE CREW SENT TO PLANT AND PUMPED OFF REMAINING LOAD. INSPECTION OF TANK REVEALED THAT RUBBER LINER HAD FAILED ALLOWING THE CORROSIVE PRODUCT TO EAT A HOLE IN METAL. TRAILER WAS DECOMMISSIONED. ALL PRODUCT NOT CAUGHT IN BUCKETS WAS PROPERLY CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED OF.

WE WERE LOADING THIS SHIPMENT OUT OF BIRMINGHAM. OUR DOCKMAN WENT TO MOVE THIS DRUM WITH THE DRUM TRUCK AND STRUCK A HOLE IN IT. WE NOTICED THIS LEAKING AND TURNED THE DRUM UPSIDE DOWN AND TAPED IT. WE SENT THIS DRUM ON TO BIRMINGHAM.

PRODUCT IN THE PROCESS OF BEING LOADED INTO TANK - SHIPPER HAD CARBOLITE MIXED WITH THE BENZINE. CARBOLITE HAD A CHEMICAL REACTION WITH THE ALUMIUM TANK. PRODUCT MELTED HOLES THROUGH BOTH SIDES OF TANK. NO PRODUCT RELEASED ONTO GROUND OR ANYWHERE. REPORTED DUE TO THE SIGNIFICANCE OF THE INCIDENT.

column168: OUR DRIVER HAD HIS VEHICLE  LOADED AT A COMPETITOR LOCATION.  THE CARGO TANK WAS SLIGHTLY OVERLOADED.  FOLLOWING THE LOADING, THE DRIVER PROCEEDED TO HIS LAYOVER POINT WHERE HE PARKED THE VEHICLE.  THE PARKING LOT WAS SUCH THAT THE VEHICLE WAS ON A SLIGHT INCLINE WHICH RESULTED IN THE LIQUID LEVEL RISING ABOVE THE LEVEL OF THE ROAD RELIEF VALVE INLET PIPE INSIDE THE CARGO TANK.  AFTER THE UNIT WAS PARKED FOR 3 HOURS, LIQUID BEGAN TO BE EMITTED FROM THE ROAD RELIEF VALVE, THE CARGO TANK WAS SECURED.  THE UNIT WAS THEN PARKED ON A LEVEL AREA OF THE PARKING LOT.  NO FURTHER INCIDENT OCCURRED.

DURING UNLOADING OF PICK-UP UNIT, DOCKMAN PUNCTURED 2 55-GALLON DRUMS (NEAR THE BOTTOM) WITH FORK BLADES.  CONTENTS OF ONE DRUM COMPLETELY LOST AND APPPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS LOST FROM 2ND DRUM.  SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED, CLEANED UP AND RESIDUE SECURED IN DRUMS TO AWAIT DISPOSAL. SHIPPPER DOES NOT WANT ANY SALVAGABLE PRODUCT RETURNED.  NO OTHER SHIPMENTS WERE INVOLVED.  CLEAN HARBORS WAS RECRUITED TO HANDLE WASTE DISPOSAL, WHICH IS COVERED BY STATE MANIFEST DOCUMENT #MA G 251481. APPROPRAIATE STEPS HAVE BEEN TAKEN TO ENSURE THAT ALL FREIGHT IN ORDER TO AVOID THIS INCIDENT FROM OCCURING AGAIN.

column168: THE DRIVER, JACK HEAD, STOPPED TO UNLOAD THE SHIPMENT AT THE CONSIGNEE AND DISCOVERED ONE PLASTIC DRUM HAD DEVELOPED A VERY SMALL LEAK.  IT WAS DETERMINED A NAIL HEAD IN THE SKID HOLDING THE SHIPMENT WAS PROTRUDING JUST ENOUGH TO RUB A SMALL HOLE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE PLASTIC DRUM.  ABOUT 0.5 CUP OF MATERIAL LEAKED AND WAS WIPED UP.  THE DRUM WAS TURNED OVER, SECURED AND BROUGHT BACK TO THE TERMINAL.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED, AND THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PUT IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND SENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER 10/15/94.  THE TRAILER WAS WASHED OUT.

0DURING TRANSPORTATION, THE WOODEN CRATE WHICH HELD THE 5-GALLON CARBOY'S BROKE, ALLOWING ONE CONTAINER TO FALL THROUGH.  WHEN UNLOADING THE CRATE, THE FORKLIFT PUNCTURED THE CARBOY, RELEASING THE MATERIAL.  NEW CRATES HAVE BEEN SUPPLIED FOR FUTURE TRANSPORTING OF 5-GALLONS CARBOYS. column168: COMPANY TRUCK LOADED WITH GENERAL FREIGHT (COMMON CARRIER).  55-GALLON DRUMS WERE LOADED IN THE VERY FRONT OF TRUCK AND SECURED FOR TRANSPORT. ALSO LOADED ON TRUCK WERE STEEL SHELVING AND STEEL SHELVING POSTS.  STEEL ITEMS WERE NOT SECURED PROPERLY, ALLOWING POSTS TO MOVE FORWARD UPON VEHICLE BRAKING AND PIERCE TOP OF ONE 55-GALLON STEEL DRUM.  ON CHECKING LOAD, DRIVER OBSERVED LEAK.  DRIVER PARKED IN A CLEAR AREA AND CONTACTED HIS SUPERVISOR.  DRIVER MANAGED SITE AND VEHICLE UNTIL HAZ WASTE CLEAN UP CREW ARRIVED.  SPILL WAS CONFINED TO VEHICLE.  DISPOSAL WAS MADE OF DRUM, ABSORBENT MATERIAL, AND ASSOCIATED CARDBOARD DESCRIBED AS TRASH (SEE HAZ WASTE MANIFEST).  TO IMPROVE FUTURE HANDLING AND LOADING, ALL CURRENT PROCEDURES WERE REVIEWED.  LOADING PERSONNEL ARE BEING RETRAINED. SUPERVISORS ARE NOW REQUIRED TO VISUALLY INSPECT ANY AND ALL LOADS CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  ANY FREIGHT NOT PACKAGED (EG. STEEL POSTS) ARE TO BE SECURED PROPERLY TO PREVENT ANY MOVEMENT DURING TRANSPORTATION.

CAR UTLX 57922 NOTED WITH LEAKING PRODUCT ON SIDE OF CAR.  CAR ISOLATED FOR INVESTIGATION.  INVESTIGATION BY GENERAL FOREMAN, P E GOLEMBECK, FOUND A MISALIGNED MANWAY GASKET.  GOLEMBECK REPOSITIONED GASKET AND RELEASED CAR. CAR SAFE FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.

DOCK ASSOCIATE WAS USING THE TOWMOTOR TO PLACE A LIGHT PALLET ON TOP OF THE 55-GALLON DRUM.  A PART OF THE TOWMOTOR BOOM PUNCTURED THE SIDE OF THE DRUM, CAUSING MATERIAL TO LEAK.  THE HOLE WAS PLUGGED WITH SHRINKWRAP UNTIL THE PALLET COULD BE TAKEN OFF THE DRUM, AND IT COULD BE PLACED ON ITS SIDE TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE.  CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED, AND THEY, IN TURN, CALLED THE SHIPPER (HULS AMERICA, INC.) FOR FURTHER INSTRUCTIONS. JOHN MAHAN, WITH THE SHIPPER, ADVISED THAT THE SPILL WAS SO SMALL WITH THE BULK OF THE PRODUCT CONTAINED IN THE DRUM, THE MATERIAL WOULD EVAPORATE OVER THE WEEKEND.  PER HIS INSTRUCTIONS, THE TRAILER WAS PLACED ON THE SERVICE CENTER YARD TO AIR OUT.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER PER JOHN'S INSTRUCTIONS.

THIS CARTON HAD BEEN LOADED TO ONE SIDE OF THE TRAILER.  WHEN THE TOWMOTOR OPERATOR CAME INTO THE TRAILER LOADING ANOTHER SHIPMENT, HE ACCIDENTALLY RAN THE TOWMOTOR INTO THIS CARTON, BURSTING THE BOTTLE INSIDE.  THE AREA WAS CLEARED OF ALL PERSONNEL, AND THE SHIPPER (J T BAKER CO.) WAS NOTIFIED.  THEY SENT A CREW TO THE FACILITY TO HANDLE THE CLEANUP OF THE TRAILER AND DISPOSE OF REMAINING PRODUCT.  THE TOWMOTOR OPERATOR RECEIVED ADDITIONAL TRAINING IN TOWMOTOR SAFETY.

column168: ACCORDING TO AVAILABLE INFORMATION AT THE TIME OF THIS REPORT, UNIT #1 WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON INTERSTATE 75, IN ROCKCASTLE COUNTY. UNIT 1 LEFT THE ROADWAY AFTER LOSING CONTROL OF HIS VEHICLE, STRUCK AN EARTH EMBANKMENT, OVERTUNED ON ITS SIDE, AND CAME TO FINAL REST AGAINST THE EARTH EMBANKMENT, ON THE SOUTHBOUND SIDE OF INTERSTATE 75. THE CAUSE OF UNIT 1 LOSING CONTROL OF HIS VEHICLE IS STILL UNDER INVESTIGATION AT THIS TIME. IT HAS BEEN STATED BY AT LEAST ONE WITNESS THAT THE OPERATOR OF UNIT 1 INDICATED THAT HE WAS OVERCOME BY FUMES FROM THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL THAT HE WAS TRANSPORTING, AND THIS CAUSED HIM TO LOSE CONTROL OF HIS VEHICLE. THIS CLAIM IS CURRENTLY UNSUBSTANTIATED, AND IS UNDER INVESTIGATION. SEVERAL WITNESS INTERVIEWS ARE STILL PENDING, AS IS A STATEMENT FROM THE OPERATOR OF UNIT 1. AN EXAMINATION OF THE ROADWAY ON 10-30-94, SHOWED NO VISIBLE TIRE MARKS OR OTHER PHYSICAL EVIDENCE TO SUGGEST THAT UNIT 1 MADE ANY PRE-IMPACT MANUEVERING OR BRAKING. NO OTHER VEHICLES WERE STRUCK BY UNIT 1, AND UNIT 1 WAS REMOVED FROM ITS AREA OF FINAL REST BEFORE I WAS PERMITTED TO EXAMINE THE ACCIDENT SCENE. THIS WAS DUE TO THE RISK OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL UNIT 1 WAS CARRYING. A THOROUGH EXAMINATION AND INSPECTION OF UNIT 1 IS ALSO NOT POSSIBLE DUE TO THE RISK OF POSSIBLE CONTAMINATION FROM THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. THE SHIPPING PAPERS AND LOG BOOK FOR UNIT 1 ARE SUPPOSELY STILL INSIDE THE VEHICLE. EXAMINATION AND PHOTOGRAPHING OF THE SCENE AND UNIT WERE NOT POSSIBLE AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT, DUE TO THE RISK OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL, NOR WERE MEASUREMENTS. ALL MEASUREMENTS WILL BE RUDIMENTARY AND APPROXIMATE. I WAS UNABLE TO LOCATE OR IDENTIFY ANY PHYSICAL EVIDENCE TO PREPARE SPEED ESTIMATES AND AREA OF IMPACT AND FINAL REST WILL ALSO BE APPROXIMATE. WITHOUT AN INSPECTION OF THE VEHICLE, I WILL ALSO BE UNABLE TO DETERMINE IF ANY MECHANICAL MALFUNCTION RESULTED IN UNIT 1'S LOSS OF CONTROL, AND CAUSED THE ACCIDENT. SEVERAL INTERVIEWS ARE STILL PENDING, AND THE LIST OF WITNESSES I HAVE PROVIDED MAY BE ADDED TO, OR DELETED FROM, BASED ON THE INFORMATION THEY PROVIDE ME. THEY WERE GIVEN TO ME AS POSSIBLE WITNESSES AND WILL BE INTERVIEWED AND THEIR STATEMENTS ADDED TO SUPPLEMENTARIES OF THIS REPORT. AN INTERVIEW WITH THE OPERATOR OF UNIT 1 IS ALSO STILL PENDING. DUE TO HIS INJURIES, AN INTERVIEW WAS NOT POSSIBLE AT THE TIME THAT THIS REPORT WAS FILED. A CHEMICAL TEST WAS NOT CONDUCTED ON THE OPERATOR OF UNIT 1, SINCE DURING THE INTERVIEWS WITH EMS PERSONNEL, THEY INDICATED TO ME THAT THEY DETECTED NO ODOR OR PRESENCE OF ALCOHOLIC BEVERAGE ON OR ABOUT THE PERSON OF THE OPERATOR OF UNIT 1. THE OBSERVATIONS I WAS ABLE TO MAKE ALSO GAVE ME NO INDICATIONS OF POSSIBLE ALCOHOL INVOLVEMENT. THE OPERATOR OF UNIT 1 WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE BEREA HOSPITAL AND THEN TRANSFERRED TO THE U.K. MEDICAL CENTER IN LEXINGTON, KY. FOR FURTHER TREATMENT. IT IS POSSIBLE THAT A BLOOD ALCOHOL AND DRUM SCREEN WAS PERFORMED AT ONE OF THESE FACILITIES. ALSO, I WAS NOT NOTIFIED AND R

column168: THE DRIVER STARTED PUMPING PRODUCT OFF WHEN THE CAP ON THE OFF SIDE OF THE PUMPING TEE CAME OFF WHEN THE EARS VIBRATED LOOSE.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN A WATER PUDDLE, SPILL PADS WERE USED TO SOAK UP THE PRODUCT AND PUT INTO A 5 GALLON BUCKET.  CURT ANDERSON FROM THE ESKO OFFICE WAS CALLED AND HE CALLED THE MN DUTY OFFICER (MARK) AT 11:00AM.  HE WENT TO THE SPILL SITE AND THEN CALLED THE MN DUTY OFFICER AGAIN AND SPOKE WITH DAN HANNAN.  DAN SAID TO PICK UP THE BAD SOIL AND BRING IT TO OUR ESKO YARD AND SPREAD IT THIN.  NO PRODUCT GOT INTO THE STREETS OR THE SEWER. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOT CALLED.

column168: DRIVER DISCOVERED, WHILE APPROACHING A STOP SIGN, FUEL COMING OUT OF GRAVITY PIPE ON RIGHT SIDE OF VEHICLE.  DRIVER STOPPED VEHICLE AND SAW CAP HAD COME LOOSE & EVIDENCE SOMEONE HAD TAMPERED WITH VALVE HANDLE LEAVING IT IN SLIGHT OPEN POSITION.  DRIVER IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED DISPATCH OFFICE OF INCIDENT BY RADIO AND RECEIVED INSTRUCTIONS PER HAZARDOUS REGULATIONS. D.E.R OF REGIONAL OFFICE WAS THEN CONTACTED AND A CLEANUP CREW SENT TO SCENE WITHIN THE HOUR.  D.E.R. GAVE FINAL APPROVAL ON CLEAN UP WORK & SAID WE DID AN OUTSTANDING JOB.  NO FURTHER ACTION WAS TAKEN AS INCIDENT WAS A FREAK ACCIDENT.  CAP ON TRUCK PIPE HAS BEEN SECURED WITH A PAD LOCK TO PREVENT FUTURE PROBLEMS.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS PUMPING OFF PRODUCT AT THE CONSIGNEE.  EMPLOYEE MISTAKENLY CLOSED THE VALVE TO THEIR TANK WHICH RESULTED IN OUR HOSE BURSTING AND A SMALL LOSS OF MATERIAL.
PRODUCT SPRAYED OUT OF PRODUCT HOSE WHEN IT WAS DISCONNECTED FROM STORAGE TANK.  PRESSURE WAS NOT BLEED OFF OF HOSE AS IT SHOULD HAVE BEEN BEFORE DISCONNECTING.  PLANT PERSONNEL CLEANED UP SPILL.

column168: WHEN PLACED ON THE CONVEYOR BELT, LIQUID POURED OUT THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX. THE UNDAMAGED BOTTLE WAS RTS'D AFTER REPACKING AND THE CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS DISPOSED OF USING PROPER DAMAGED PACKAGE PROCESSING AND DISPOSAL PROCEDURES.

column168: TRACTOR-TRAILER TRAVELING WEST ON ROUTE 414. AS THE UNIT CAME OUT OF A CURVE THE LOAD SHIFTED CAUSING THE UNIT TO ROLL ON ITS RIGHT SIDE OVER THE GUARD RAIL. THE TRAILER WAS PUNCTURED ON THE RIGHT REAR SIDE RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 2,300 GALLONS OF TOLUENE. THE BRADFORD COUNTY EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT UNIT CONTACTED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CLEAN-UP TEAM TO RESPOND TO THE INCIDENT. MEMBERS OF THE PENNSYLVANIA D.E.R. WERE ON THE SCENE. CARRIER PERSONNEL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE TO ASSIST IN THE CLEAN-UP. MATERIAL REMAINING IN THE TRAILER WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER OF THE CARRIER'S TANK TRAILERS BY CARRIER PERSONNEL.
THE DRIVER DROPPED THE HOSE BEFORE IT WAS COMPLETELY DRAINED. THE FILL IS ABOVE THE OUTLET ON THE TRAILER; THEREFORE, THE HOSE REMAINS FULL.

ON FRIDAY, OCTOBER 7, 1994, DELTA DISTRIBUTORS, INCORPORATED DRIVER, HAROLD CANNON, WAS MAKING A DELIVERY TO A CUSTOMER, VECOM PRODUCTION USA, LTD, IN JEFFERSON, LOUISIANA.  THE DRIVER NOTICED ONE OF THE TANKS HAD A SMALL DRIP AROUND THE VALVE AREA. THE DRIVER PROCEEDED TO CHECK THE VALVE ASSEMBLY TO SEE IF SOMETHING MAY HAVE BEEN BROKEN OR LOOSE.  WHEN HE DID, THE COMPLETE PIPING AND VALVE ASSEMBLE BROKE APART FROM THE INTERNAL PART OF THE TANK.  THE JEFFERSON PARISH EMERGENCY RESPONSE WERE NOTIFIED AND DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE, ALONG WITH THE DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY.  BOTH DEPARTMENTS WITNESSED THE NEUTRALIZATION AND SPILL CLEAN UP.  ESTIMATED LOSS 110 GALLONS OF 50% SODIUM HYDROXIDE/50% WATER, WHICH RELEASED 700 POUNDS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE.

column168: ON 100194 AT APPROXIMATELY 1130AM, REEDER RECEIVED A CALL FROM MTO LABELLO THAT THE ABOVE CAR WAS SLOSHING LIQUID FROM THE TOP WHEN IT WAS MOVED. REEDER ADVISED LABELLO THAT THE CAR COULD BE SAFETY MOVED TO AN ISOLATED LOCATION IF THE CREW USED A COVER CAR AND HANDLED THE CAR CAREFULLY.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED TO A SIDE TRACK FOR REPAIR.  REEDER ARRIVED AND DISCOVERED THAT THE CDC 100# FRANGIBLE DISC HAD FAILED.  THE DISC WAS LOCATED NEAR THE MANWAY.  THE DISC WAS REPLACED IN KIND AN THE CAR RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT WITHOUT DELAY.

MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D.A. LOW, WAS CONTACTED BY YARD MASTER, DENVER, COLORADO, THAT TANK CAR FLIX 8025, NORTH END TRAIN YARD 5, WAS NOTED LEAKING BY CAR MAN PHIL KEYSER.  PHIL ADVISED THAT HE WAS RETURNING TO OFFICE ACCOUNT OF AMMONIA ANHYDROUS, INHALATION.  MANAGER, D.O. LOW, SECURED TWO NUT PACKING GLAND ON 'B' END DISCHARGE 2-INCH BALL VALVE.  2 AND 1/2 TURNS WERE TAKEN TO SECURE LEAK.  IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT CARMAN PHIL KEYSER WAS TRANSPORTED BY CAR FOREMAN TO ST. ANTHONYS CENTRAL HOSPITAL AT 0315 HOURS, 10/02/94 AND RELEASED MORNING OF SAME DATE.  PERSONAL INJURY REPORTED UNDER INCIDENT NUMBER 1094FM001.  MR. KEYSET RECEIVED A PRECRIPTION AND WORKED 5 DAYS OF RESTRICTED ACTIVITY. ALSO, IT HAD RAINED PRIOR MANAGER LOW'S ARRIVAL AND RAIN WATER HAD POOLED ON GROUND, WITH TEMPERATURE AT 49 DEGREES ABOVE ZERO AND PARTLY CLOUDY. JOE MALZZIO, CHEMTREC FILE #0440, JACK CURY, FARMLAND AND DAN SLINGER, STRATTON EQUITY COOP, WERE NOTIFIED OF EXCEPTION.

REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY DEANN L. WHITELEY, PORTLAND, OR., WAS NOTIFIED BY MANAGER YARD OPERATIONS PETER MARTIN, STOCKTON, CA., THAT LIQUID WAS RUNNING DOWN THE SIDES OF TANK CAR NATX 38405, ALCOHOLIC BEVERGES, SPOTTED UNION PACIFIC STOCKTON YARD.  HE CONTACTED SPECIAL AGENT.  HAZARDOUS MATERIALS BARRY BALLANCE,STOCKTON, CA. WHO RESPONDED AND FOUND NUTS ON THE THREADED STUDS SECURING THE LIQUID EDUCATION VALVE TO THE TANK CAR LOOSE.  SAHM BALLANCE BLED OFF INTERNAL PRESSURE THROUGH VACCUM RELEIF VALVE SIGNIFICANTLY SLOWING FLOW OF LIQUID AND THEN TIGHTENED NUTS WHICH STOPPED FLOW COMPLETELY.  IT WAS NECESSARY FOR BALLANCE TO REMOVE INTACT SHIPPERS SEAL FROM HINGED HOUSING TO GAIN ACCESS TO LIQUID VALVE AND VACCUM RELEIF VALVE.  SEAL NUMBER WAS NOT RECORDED.  JOHN WOHLGEMUTH, MIDWEST GRAIN PRODUCTS WAS FURNISHED DETAILS. CHEMTREC WAS NOT NOTIFIED.  THE LEAKING MATERIAL EVAPORATED BEFORE IMPACTING GROUND AND DID NOT CREATE ANY ENVIRONMENTAL HAZARD.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1155 HOURS OF MONDAY, 10/03/94, YARD PERSONNEL AT UPRR LIVONIA YARD OBSERVED LIQUID SLOSHING FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR DURING MOVEMENT.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AT LIVONIA WITHOUT INCIDENT AND REGIONAL MANAGER-CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY T.M. ROBINSON WAS NOTIFIED. ROBINSON INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK WAS A FAILED FRANGIBLE DISC IN THE SAFETY VALVE ASSEMBLY.  THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY WAS LOCATED ON IT'S OWN NOZZLE, WITHIN THE WORKING PLATFORM, TOWARD THE "A" END OF THE CAR NEXT TO THE MAWAY.  THE FAILED DISC WAS A BS&B, 4 INCH, TYPE DV, STAINLESS STEEL AND TEFLON COMPOSITION, RATED AT 61 PSIG. ROBINSON REPLACED THE DISC WITH A DISC OF SIMILAR SPECIFICATIONS AND THIS PROPERLY SECURED THE CAR FOR MOVEMENT.

UPRR NEY YARDMASTER WILLIE TROJACK REPORTED THAT TANK CAR NDYX34324 WAS LEAKING VAPOR FROM THE TOP.  THE CAR WAS LOCATED IN TRACK 6, NEY YARD. UPRR CTS MANAGER ARLA ROQUET RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND FOUND A LOOSE LIQUID LINE PLUG AND THE CONTROL VALVE HAND WHEEL ON THE GAUGING DEVICE WAS NOT TIGHT.  THESE WERE TIGHTENED AND NO FURTHER ODOR WAS NOTED. CABLE SEAL #047176 WAS REMOVED FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING.  CABLE SEAL UPRR #043685 WAS APPLIED TO THE HOUSING TO SECURE THE CAR.

ON WEDNESDAY, 10/5/94, TANK CAR CHVX291006 WAS INSPECTED AT THE UPRR YARD AT LIVONIA, L BY FRA INSPECTORS, WM A. FERNAU AND JIM DUNCAN.  THE CAR WAS FOUND TO HAVE A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT LEAKING PAST THE PLUG OF THE LIQUID VALVE.  THIS WAS REPORTED TO UPRR MANAGER OF MECH. MNTUNCE G. SHORT.  SHORT IN TURN REPORTED THIS TO UPRR REGINOAL MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANS. SAFETY T.M. ROBINSON.  THE VALVE PLUG WAS TIGHTENED ABOUT ONE TURN AND THIS SECURED THE CAR FROM LEAKING.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED ONTO DESTINATION WITH OUT DELAY.  ROBINSON CONTACTED JOE DEBMNAM OF CHEMTREC, REPORT #31522.  ROBINSON ALSO SPOKE WITH ME. DANNY LEVASSUAR, HEAD OPERATOR FOR CHEVRON CHEMICAL AT OAK POINT, LOUISIANA.

S/A BALLANCE RECEIVED A REPORT FROM KENT AT UPMF THAT CONTAINER GSTU-865589 ARRIVED LEAKING AND IS NOW ON TRACK 802.  S/A, BALLANCE ARRIVED AND MEET WITH THOMAS MORGAN OF MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL.  MORGAN PROVIDED THE FOLLOWING INFORMATION.  ARRIVED AND OPENED DOORS TO COTNAINER, FOUND LITTLE BLOCKING AND BO RACING.  THE LEAKING PRODUCT WA FOUND ON THE SECONE PALLET IN.  THE PRODUCT ON THE PALET WAS SHRINK WERPPED AND SECURED TO THE PALLET.  THE 18 DRUMS ON THE PALLET APPEATED TO HAVE COLAPSED IN ON THEMSELVES.  THERE WERE TWO TYPES OF DRUMS ON THE SAME PALLET.  THE DRUMS CONTAINED THE SAME PRODUCT.  THE DRUMS THAT DID NOT LEAK WERE DOT APPROVED.  THE DRUMS THAT FAILED HAD NO DOT STAMP.  THE DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED AND PLACED BACK INTO THE CONTAINER.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS ALLOWED TO DRY.  THE PALLETS WERE PLACED BACK INTO THE CONTAINER ON PLASTIC.  HELEN OF APL WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THE INCIDENT.  SHE WAS ALSO ADVISED SHE NEEDED TO HAVE THE FLOOR BOARDS REPLACED.

column168: ON 011294 AT APPROXIMATELY 500AM A SWITCHMAN NOTICED THE ABOVE CONTAINER HAD THE RIGHT REAR DOOR PUSHED OPEN AND WAS LEAKING LIQUID FROM THE REAR DOORS.  THE CONTAINER WAS PLACARDED POISON.  HE NOTIFIED MTO PENNINGTON WHO CALLED REEDER.  PENNINGTON ARRANGED TO HAVE THE CONTAINER, ON ITS FLATCAR MOVED TO THE LEY ROAD TEAM TRACK WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED AND RESPONDERS WHO WOULD HAVE GOOD ACCESS.  THE CONTAINER AND FLATCAR WERE WET WITH LIQUID.  THE CONTAINER WAS LOADED WITH A LIQUID PESTICIDE.  USING PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT, RESPONDERS OPENED THE DOORS TO DETERMINE THE EXTENT OF THE DAMAGE.  INSIDE SERVERAL BOARDS AND A SHEET OF PLYWOOD WERE FOUND ON THE FLOOR.  INSIDE WERE 80 200 LITER STEEL DRUMS.  SEVERAL HAD BEEN CRUSHED THOUGH THEY WERE NOT LEAKING.  ONE DRUM HAD A NAIL HOLE NEAR THE BOTTOM. ABOVE THE CHIME AND HAD LOST ALL ITS CONTENTS.  THE HOLE WAS PLUGGED AND THE DRUM OVERPACKED.  THIRTEEN OF THE DAMAGED DRUMS WERE ALSO OVERPACKED FOR SAFETY, THOUGH THEY WERE NOT LEAKING.  THE MANUFACTURER STATED THE PRODUCT COULD BE NEUTRALIZED WITH A 10% HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION (EITHER SODIUM OR CALCIUM).  A 50% SOLUTION WAS USED TO RINSE THE CONTAINER AND FLAT CAR.  ALL WASTE LIQUIDS WERE COLLECTED USING ABSORBANTS.  THE CONTAMINATED AREAS OF THE BALLAST WERE TREATED WITH SODE ASH GRANULES THEN SOAKED WITH WATER TO COMPLETE THE PROCESS.  FINAL DISPOSTION OF THE DRUMS WILL BE DETERMINED BY THE SHIPPER.

CAR DAMAGED IN DERAILMENT AT PIOLET NEVADA, DURING THE EVENING HOURS OF THE 10TH OF OCTOBER.  INSPECTION CONDUCTED ON THE MORNING OF THE 11TH.  AT 0900 HRS.  FINDING AS FOLLOWS, CAR WAS MISSING PLACARDS ON BOTH LEFT AND RIGHT SIDES AND ON THE B-END OF THE CAR, ALL PLACARDS WERE REPLACED BY GMR. RODABROUGH.  CONTINUED INSPECTION REVEALED LEAK FROM THE PACKING GLAND NUT ON THE GAUGING DEVICE, THIS WAS AN EXTREMELY MINOR LEAK, COULD BE DETECTED BY ODOR ONLY AND WAS EASILY CORRECTED BY TIGHTENING THE THUMB SCREW.  CAR TO BE SENT TO SHOP FOR REPAIR TO SAFETY APPLIANCES AND RUNNING GEAR, TANK NOT DAMAGED.

ON 101294 AT APPROXIMATELY 8PM CARMEN WERE WORKING ON THE ABOVE CAR AT THE SETTEGAST YARD RIP TRACK.   ONE OF THE WORKERS NOTICED AN ODOR COMING FROM THE CAR.  A CHECK WITH A FLAMMABLE GAS DETECTOR INDICATED THE LEAK WAS ON THE TOP OF THE CAR INSIDE THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING.  REEDER WAS NOTIFIED AND ARRIVED AT 9PM.  THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK WAS THE SAFETY RELEIF VALVE. REEDER DISCOVERED THE NUTS HOLDING THE VALVE WERE NOT COMPLETELY TIGHT. TURNING EACH NUT ABOUT 1/8 TO 1/4 TURN STOPPED THE LEAK.  CARMEN CONTINUED WITH THEIR REPAIRS.

A.  THE ACCIDENT HAPPENED ON THE EAST BOUND I-10 FREEWAY BETWEEN DUDLEY STREET AND GAREY AVENUE IN THE CITY OF POMONA, CA; AT APPROXIMATELY 8:00 A.M. KENNY DIAZ (SUN-RAY TESTING EMPLOYEE) WAS ON HIS WAY TO NORTHWEST PIPE AND CASING CO. IN ADELANTO, CA. (B).  THE ACCIDENT WAS CAUSED BY A BLOWOUT IN THE RIGHT REAR TIRE ON ONE OF OUR FIELD RADIOGRAPHY UNITS.  THE BLOWOUT DESTROYED THE TIRE AND THE TRUCK WAS RUNNING ON THE TIRE RIM ONLY. AS THE DRIVER WAS STEERING THE TRUCK TO THE RIGHT EMERGENCY LANE THE TRUCK STARTED SWAYING BACK AND FORTH AND TIPPED ON IT'S LEFT (DRIVER) SIDE AND SKIDDED ACROSS THE FREEWAY AND INTO THE CONCRETE RETAINING WALL, IN THE PROCESS THE DARKROOM (CAMPER) BROKE AWAY FROM THE TRUCK.  WHEN THE TRUCK HIT THE RETAINING WALL, THE IMPACT WITH THE WALL PUT THE TRUCK BACK ON IT'S WHEELS.  THE TIRE THAT FAILED WAS IN GOOD CONDITION PRIOR TO THE BLOWOUT.  (C)  NO OTHER VEHICLE WAS INVOLVED IN THE ACCIDENT AND THERE WERE NO INJURIES AS A RESULT OF THE ACCIDENT.  (D) THE TRUCK WAS CARRYING A 73 CURIE SOURCE OF RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, IRIDIUM 192. THE SEALED SOURCE WAS IN A AMERTEST MODEL 660 B GAMMA RAY PROJECTOR S/N B2136, TYPE-B SHIPPING CONTAINER.  AS SOON AS THE DRIVER GOT OUT OF THE TRUCK HE SURVEYED THE PORTABLE DARKROOM WHICH CONTAINED THE SOURCE AND HE FOUND THE READINGS TO BE NORMAL.  HE CALLED THE A.R.S.O., BERT JERSILD (FROM A MOTORIST CELLULAR CAR PHONE) AND REPORTED THE ACCIDENT, HE ALSO CALLED THE C.H.P. AND REPORTED THE ACCIDENT AND THAT THE TRUCK CONTAINED RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL AND THAT A SURVEY OF THE RADIOACTIVE SOURCE INDICATED THE AREA WAS SAFE.  (F) BERT JERSILD (SUN-RAY TESTING A.R.S.O.) DISPATCHED CLIFF BARBER, A.S.R.T. SENIOR RADIOGRAPHER TO THE ACCIDENT SCENE IN A FIELD RADIOGRAPHY UNIT TO PICK UP THE RADIOACTIVE SOURCE.  (G) THE C.H.P., FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE HAZ-MET PERSONNEL DECIDED TO SHUT DOWN THE FREEWAY TO ASSURE SAFETY.  SUN-RAY TESTING PERSONNEL ASSURED THEM THAT THERE WAS NO DANGER TO THE PUBLIC BUT IT DID NOT CHANGE THEIR MINDS.  (H) AT THE ACCIDENT SCENE, CLIFF BARBER (S.R.T.) USING THE HAZ-MET CHIEFS CAR PHONE, TALKED TO A LADY FROM THE COUNTY RADIOLOGIC HEALTH DEPT.  (CLIFF THOUGHT HE WAS TALKING TO A LADY FROM THE STATE RADIOLOGIC HEALTH OFFICE) AND BASED ON WHAT HE TOLD HER THE AUTHORITIES DECIDED TO LET CLIFF REMOVE THE RADIOACTIVE SOURCE FROM THE FIELD DARK ROOM AND EXAMINE IT.  THE OUTER TRANSPORT BOX AND THE PROJECTOR WERE NOT DAMAGED.  APPROXIMATELY TWO (2) HOURS AFTER ARRIVING AT THE ACCIDENT SCENE CLIFF WAS ALLOWED TO RETURN TO SUN-RAY TESTING OFFICE WITH THE SOURCE.  THE PROJECTOR WAS OPERATED AT SUN-RAY TESTING LAB AND FOUND TO BE IN PERFECT WORKING CONDITION.  (I) ON WEDNESDAY, OCTOBER 19, 1994, I NOTIFIED THE DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION (BY PHONE) AS REQUIRED BY TITLE 49 C.F.R. 171.15 (V) " ONE OR MORE MAJOR TRANSPORATION ARTERIES OR FACILITIES ARE CLOSED OR SHUTDOWN FOR ONE HOUR OR MORE".  THIS WOULD HAVE BEEN DONE SOONER BUT I WAS ON VACATION AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT AND THA A.R
WHILE UNLOADING A TRAILER, TWO POLY DRUMS WERE FOUND SEEPING FROM THE CLOSURE.  AN INSPECTION REVEALED A FAULTY CLOSURE AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.  THE DRUMS WERE RETURNED FOR CLAIM CREDIT.

column168: DEAN C COOPER MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED THAT A TANK CAR WAS NOTED LEAKING DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS IN THE YERMO CALIFORNIA YARD.  THE CAR WAS SET TO THE CABOOSE TRACK AND ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  THIS CAR ARRIVED YERMO ON THE HKYR-10 AT 0710 HOURS, THURSDAY, OCTOBER 13, 1994.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE YERMO YARD FACILITY, INSPECTED THE CAR, AND DEVELOPED THE PRIMARY SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM A BURST RUPTURE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT.  WHILE INSPECTING THE SAFETY VENT, THE FOLLOWING EXCEPTIONS WERE NOTED; THE COVER CAP FOR THE SAFETY VENT WAS ONLY HELD IN PLACED BY THE KEEPER PIN AS THE HINGE WELD HAD BEEN BROKEN; THE WHOLE SAFETY VENT WAS LOOSE AND COULD BE TURNED BY HAND (VENT MOUNTED CENTER ON THE MANWAY COVER PLATE); THE RETAINER FOR THE RUPTURE DISC WAS PLACED UPSIDE DOWN.  THE SAFETY VENT, A STANDARD MIDLAND BAFFLE STYLE, WAS DISASSEMBLED AND THE BURST DISC REPLACED WITH A LIKE TYPE BS&B 100 POUND STAINLESS/TEFLON DISC.  THE SAFETY VENT WAS PROPERLY REASSEMBLED AND TIGHTENED.  THE CAP COVER WAS WIRED DOWN TO HOLD IT IN PLACE.  WHILE INSPECTING THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS, ALSO FOUND FOUR OF THE SIX SWING BOLTS ON THE MANWAY COVER PLATE LOOSE WHICH COULD BE TURNED BY HAND.  THEY WERE ALSO PROPERLY SECURED.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSED AND TO THE SHIPPER FOR CORROSIVE ACTION.

ON 10/28/94 AT APPROXIMATELY 0319 HRS, I, KAREN NICHOLS/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR OF ABX AIR, INC, 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON OH 45177 INVESTIGATED A LEAKING SHIPMENT IN OUR SORT FACILITY OF THE SAME ADDRESS.  THE SHIPMENT WAS PACKAGED IN A FIBREBOARD BOX THAT HAD NO HAZARD MARKINGS OR LABELS ON IT OTHER THAT "ORM-D CONSUMER COMMODITY"  STAMPED PACKAGING TAPE ACCROSS THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX.  THERE WAS NO ORIENTATION MARKING OR LABEL ON THE FIBREBOARD BOX.  THERE WAS NO SHIPPERS CERTIFICATIONS FOR DANAGEROUS GOODS ACCOMPANYING THE SHIPMENT.  INSIDE THE FIBREBOARD BOX I FOUND 1 GLASS BOTTLE WITH PLASTIC SCREW-TYPE CLOSURES OF 5 OZ CAPACITY.  THESE GLASS BOTTLES CONTAIN "LIQUID HEAT" ARTHRITIS AND SORE MUSCLE RUB.  1 OF 12 GLASS BOTTLES WAS BROKEN.  THE SHIPMENT IS CURRENTLY BEING HELD IN OUR HAZMAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING RELEASE BY THE FAA.
I RESPONDED TO THE SPILL WEARING PPE, IDENTIFIED CONTENTS FROM FIVE PART FORM, DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEETS, NEUTRALIZED SPILL USING SOLUSORB AND PROCESSED ACCORDING TO DMP PROCEDURES.
FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE, I REFERRED TO DAMAGED PACKAGE RESPONSE PROCEDURE, FLAMMABLE LIQUID, ABSORBED SPILL WITH SOLUSORB AND PROCESSED THROUGH DAMAGE MATERIALS PROGRAM.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER ALLOWED RIGHT TIRE TO GET OFF ON SIDE OF ROAD, THEN TRIED TO PULL BACK AND OVER CORRECTED. WHICH CAUSED TRUCK AND TRAILER TO LAY OVER ON IT'S LEFT SIDE. CYPRUS BAGDAD CO. USED A VACUVATOR TO CLEAN-UP SPILL PLUS A CLEAN-UP CREW. THE FOLLOWING ASSUMPTIONS AND CALCULATIONS WERE USED TO ESTIMATE THE AMOUNTS OF COPPER AND LEAD SULFIDE RELEASED IN THE CONCENTRATE TRUCK SPILL ON OCTOBER 20, 1994. (SEE ATTACHED). THE AUGUST COMPOSITE SAMPLE RESULTS FOR LEAD SULFIDE AND COPPER WERE USED TO CALCULATE THE TOTAL AMOUNT OF BOTH SUBSTANCES. THE AMOUNT OF LEAD SULFIDE IN THE CONCENTRATE IS EXTREMELY VARIABLE. THEREFORE, WE HAVE REQUESTED THAT A SAMPLE BE RUN FOR THE EXACT AMOUNT OF LEAD SULFIDE. THIS OPERATION WILL TAKE 1-2 HOURS. THE CONCENTRATE WEIGHTED 49,650 LBS. APPROXIMATELY 10,000 LBS REMAINS IN THE TRUCK WHICH IS ON ITS SIDE. WE WILL ATTEMPT TO RECOVER THIS AMOUNT USING A VACUUM TRUCK. IF UNSUCCESSFUL, ADDITIONAL CONCENTRATE WILL BE LOST. USING THE ENTIRE WEIGHT OF THE CONCENTRATE AND THE AUGUST COMPOSITE NUMBER OF .03 PERCENT LEAD SULFIDE, 14.7 LBS OF LEAD SULFIDE HAVE BEEN SPILLED. USING A CONSERVATIVE ESTIMATE OF 8,OOO LBS RECOVERED (NOT RELEASED) FROM THE TRUCK BODY, 12.5 LBS OF LEAD SULFIDE HAVE BEEN SPILLED. THEREFORE, THE REPORTABLE QUANTITY OF 10 LBS MAY HAVE BEEN EXCEEDED. APPROXIMATELY 20 PERCENT OF THE COPPER IN THE CONCENTRATE RUNS BELOW 250 MESH IN SIZE WHICH IS SUBSTANTIALLY EQUIVALENT TO THE .004 INCH EXEMPTION FROM REPORTING. USING THE ABOVE FIGURES FOR AMOUNT RELEASED FROM THE TRUCK, 3150 LBS OF COPPER METAL ARE RELEASED IF NO RECOVERY OF CONCENTRATE IS MADE AND 2643 LBS OF COPPER ARE RELEASED IF 8000 LBS ARE RECOVERED. THEREFORE, THE REPORTABLE QUANTITY OF 5000 LBS HAS NOT BEEN EXCEEDED. MR. WALTER RUSNIEK OF KIMBALL AND CURRY IS LOOKING INTO THE SUBJECT OF REPORTING RESPONSIBILITY AND WILL BE DOCUMENTING THIS TODAY. THE INITIAL REVIEW SUPPORTS THE CONCLUSION THAT IT IS A TRUCKING FIRM RESPONSIBILITY. IN THE MEANTIME, WE WILL PROCEED WITH THE ANALYTICAL EFFORT ON THE CONCENTRATE AND FOLLOW UP WITH A SUBSEQUENT REPORT.

column168: ONE OF OUR DRIVERS, BILLY SMITH, WAS ENROUTE TO NATIONAL ELECTRIC CARBON CORPORATION IN FOSTORIA, OHIO WHEN HE STOPPED HIS UNIT JUST WEST OF WILLARD, OHIO ON ROUTE 224 TO CONDUCT A ROUTINE MOTOR VEHICHLE INSPECTION. HE DISCOVERED THAT ONE OF THE THE FIFTEEN GALLON DELDRUMS CONTAINING SULFURIC ACID HAD SPRUNG A LEAK AS A RESULT OF BEING PUNCTURED BY A NAIL PROTRUDING FROM THE PALLET ON WHICH IT WAS BEING TRANSPORTED. BILLY TURNED THE DELDRUM UPSIDE DOWN TO PREVENT THE RELEASE OF ANY ADDITIONAL PRODUCT AND THEN CLEANED UP THE RESIDUE AROUND THE DELDRUM ON THE PALLET. WE WILL CONTINUE TO MAKE EVERY EFFORT POSSIBLE TO ENSURE THAT ALL PRODUCT SENT OUT FOR DELIVERY IS SENT OUT ON PALLETS IN GOOD CONDITION. WE TYPICALLY REPLACED PALLETS AS THEY BECOME UNSERVICEABLE AND THIS WAS AN ISOLATED INCIDENT.

column168: ON 10-31-94, BWG RECEIVED A CALL FROM CARL THOMAS ABOUT A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL LEAK NEAR FRANKLIN, KY. ROAD DRIVER DETECTED A POSSIBLE LEAK ON TRAILER P6688, A LOUISVILLE TO MEMPHIS BREAK TRAILER. LEAK WAS VERY MINOR AND ONLY SHOWED A STRAIN ON BOTTOM FLOOR OF TRAILER. DRIVER ARRIVED IN BOWLING GREEN AT 12:20 FOR AN EVALUTION OF THE SPILL. THE LEAKING SHIPMENT WAS LOCATED. ONE OF THE 5 GALLON BUCKETS HAD BEEN PUNCTURED. LOOKED AS IF THE BUCKET HAD BEEN HIT WITH FORKLIFT OR OTHER FREIGHT. THE SKID WAS REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER AND FLOOR DRY WAS PUT DOWN TO SOAK UP SPILL. THE CONTAMINATED FLOOR DRY WAS PUT INTO A 5 GAL SALVAGE DRUM ALONG WITH THE DAMAGED BUCKET. PRO AND FLAMMABLE LIQUID WERE WRITTEN ON THIS SALVAGE DRUM. THIS SALVAGE DRUM WAS SENT WITH ORIGINAL SHIPMENT ON TRAILER TO DESTINATION. AFTER TRAILER WAS CLEANED, FLOOR DRY AND CARDBOARD WAS PUT DOWN FOR MORE SOAKING.

column168: TANK CAR CELX 11258 WAS REPORTED TO BE EMITTING AN ODOR BY YARD CONDUCTOR IN BELLEVUE, OH ON 10/18/94.  ETHYL ACRYLATE HAS AN ODOR THRESHOLD LESS THAT 1 PART PER MILLION.  EMPLOYEE WAS GIVEN REQUESTED MEDICAL ATTENTION AS CUSTOMARY UNDER COMPANY POLICY AND FOUND TO BE O.K. BY COMPANY DOCTOR. NS MECHANICAL SUPERVISORS CONDUCTED INSPECTION OF CAR AND COULD FIND NO DETECTABLE LEAK.  CARRIER PERSONNEL DISCUSSED MATTER WITH CONSIGNEE REPRESENTATIVE (BF GOODRICH, AVON LAKE, OH).  CAR WAS DETERMINED TO BE NOT LEAKING AND SECURE.  IT WAS MOVED TO FINAL DESTINATION.  FRA INSPECTOR JOE CONNELLY CALLED NS TERMINAL SUPERINTENDENT ON 10/19/94 AND ADVISED THAT NS HAD MOVED A LEAKING TANK CAR FROM INSPECTIONS BY MECHANICAL SUPERVISORS REVEALED NO DISCERNABLE RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  ON 10/20/94, TWO DAYS AFTER THE ALLEGED INCIDENT, FRA INSPECTORS CONNELLY AND NIGORSKI INSPECTED TANK CAR AT BF GOODRICH FACILITY IN AVON LAKE AND CLAIMED THAT THE CAR HAD A LEAK.  THEY REPORTED BEING ABLE TO PARTIALLY TURN A BOLT ON TOP OF THE CAR.  CARRIER CONTACTED BF GOODRICH REP DAN COLLINS AND WAS TOLD THAT BF GOODRICH WOULD NOT HAVE CONSIDERED THE CAR TO BE LEAKING.  NO WRITTEN REPORTS WERE SUBMITTED TO THE CARRIER BY FRA AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT, AND CARRIER DID NOT FILE DOT F5800.1.  THE SITUATION WAS DISCUSSED AT A 01/11/95 MEETING IN CLEVELAND AMONG FRA INSPECTORS CONNELLY AND NIGORSKI, MEMBERS OF NS HAZMAT DEPT., BELLEVUE TERMINAL SUPT., AND THE SHIPPER. DURING THIS MEETING, WE WERE ADVISED THAT HOECHST CELANESE WAS UNABLE TO CONDUCT A THROROUGH INVESTIGATION ON THIS CAR BECAUSE OF THE SOUTHERN PACIFIC DERAILED AND DAMAGED THE EMPTY CAR WHICH WAS RETURNING TO BAYPORT, TX.  HOECHST CELANESE ALSO STATED THAT THE ODOR OF THIS PRODCUT COULD BE DETECTED UP TO 15 DAYS AFTER IT CAME IN CONTACT WITH A CAR, AND THAT A ODOR SHOULD NOT NECESSARILY BE CONSIDERED AS AN "ACTIVE" RELEASE. ALTHOUGH CARRIER ASSERTS THAT TANK CAR CELX 11258 WAS NOT LEAKING @ BELLEVUE, OH, ON 10/18/94 WHEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO AVON LAKE, WE HAVE NO REASON TO QUESTION THE OBSERVATION REPORTED BY MESSRS. CONNELLY AND NIGORSKI.  FOR THIS REASON, WE ARE SUBMITTING A DOT F5800.1 REPORT FOR THE INCIDENT AT AVON LAKE.  THIS REPORT DOES NOT ANSWER ALL THE QUESTIONS, BUT AT LEAST IT ESTABLISHES A RECORD OF THE OBSERVATIONS REPORTED BY THE PRINCIPALS INVOLVED.
